1
00:00:43,420 --> 00:00:46,580
There was a demon that lived in the air.

2
00:00:47,060 --> 00:00:50,900
They said whoever challenged him
would die.

3
00:00:52,340 --> 00:00:54,260
Their controls would freeze up.

4
00:00:54,380 --> 00:00:56,820
Their planes would buffet wildly...

5
00:00:57,780 --> 00:00:59,700
and they would disintegrate.

6
00:01:04,020 --> 00:01:06,900
The demon lived at Mach 1 on the meter...

7
00:01:07,300 --> 00:01:09,580
750 miles an hour...

8
00:01:09,940 --> 00:01:12,980
where the air could no longer
move out of the way.

9
00:01:14,060 --> 00:01:19,140
He lived behind a barrier through which
they said no man could ever pass.

10
00:01:20,820 --> 00:01:24,180
They called it the sound barrier.

11
00:01:26,580 --> 00:01:28,540
Then they built a small plane...

12
00:01:28,660 --> 00:01:32,100
the X-1, to try and break the sound barrier.

13
00:01:33,100 --> 00:01:37,300
And men came to the high desert
of California to ride it.

14
00:01:41,020 --> 00:01:43,380
They were called test pilots...

15
00:01:45,020 --> 00:01:47,300
and no one knew their names.

16
00:02:02,420 --> 00:02:05,300
Okay, Whiskey Kilo 28, prepare to drop.

17
00:02:05,460 --> 00:02:08,140
Roger, Ground Control.
This is Whiskey Kilo 28...

18
00:02:08,220 --> 00:02:10,580
lowering and launching... now.

19
00:02:22,420 --> 00:02:24,340
Mach.92.

20
00:02:27,700 --> 00:02:29,620
.93.

21
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:34,100
.94.

22
00:02:35,140 --> 00:02:37,140
Hit a mild buffet there.

23
00:02:39,220 --> 00:02:40,820
Mach.95.

24
00:02:45,100 --> 00:02:46,180
.96.

25
00:02:49,860 --> 00:02:50,940
.97.

26
00:02:54,900 --> 00:02:56,140
.98!

27
00:02:59,660 --> 00:03:00,940
.99!

28
00:03:02,380 --> 00:03:05,060
WK 28, do you want to declare
an emergency?

29
00:03:05,420 --> 00:03:07,780
Negative. WK 28 is not...

30
00:03:33,100 --> 00:03:34,860
Go away.

31
00:07:16,780 --> 00:07:19,020
I was looking at the pictures on your wall.

32
00:07:19,100 --> 00:07:20,700
How come a fancy pilot...

33
00:07:20,780 --> 00:07:23,940
like Slick there,
doesn't have his picture up there?

34
00:07:24,580 --> 00:07:27,260
What do you have to do
to get your picture up there?

35
00:07:27,380 --> 00:07:29,140
You have to die, sweetie.

36
00:07:32,620 --> 00:07:35,180
Well, Yeager, you old bastard.

37
00:07:35,820 --> 00:07:40,540
Don't just stand in the doorway
like some lonesome sheepherder.

38
00:07:40,740 --> 00:07:42,780
Get your ass over here and have a drink.

39
00:07:42,860 --> 00:07:44,420
I got you something.

40
00:07:50,140 --> 00:07:51,180
Come here.

41
00:07:54,660 --> 00:07:56,300
You could be the first.

42
00:07:56,420 --> 00:07:59,300
The man who breaks the sound barrier
will be on top.

43
00:07:59,820 --> 00:08:01,340
You'd be the one they remembered.

44
00:08:01,420 --> 00:08:04,100
You're the best civilian pilot around.

45
00:08:04,180 --> 00:08:05,180
Good afternoon.

46
00:08:05,580 --> 00:08:07,020
You get that helmet?

47
00:08:10,020 --> 00:08:11,300
It might work.

48
00:08:11,580 --> 00:08:13,380
I'll look like the Galloping Ghost in it.

49
00:08:13,460 --> 00:08:16,500
Some people say the sound barrier
can't be broke.

50
00:08:17,140 --> 00:08:19,660
An engineer will tell you it's an absolute...

51
00:08:19,740 --> 00:08:21,820
like the firmness of the earth.

52
00:08:22,420 --> 00:08:25,380
The sound barrier is a farm
you can buy in the sky.

53
00:08:25,700 --> 00:08:28,740
The controls will freeze up.
You can't budge the stick.

54
00:08:28,820 --> 00:08:31,460
Anybody tries to break it will auger in.

55
00:08:33,380 --> 00:08:35,980
Well now, maybe it can't be broke.

56
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:38,340
Then again...

57
00:08:39,620 --> 00:08:41,060
maybe it can.

58
00:08:42,820 --> 00:08:46,860
Maybe it can only be broke
for a specified sum.

59
00:08:48,580 --> 00:08:49,700
How much?

60
00:08:51,940 --> 00:08:54,340
$150,000.

61
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:57,180
Come on, Slick, give us a break.

62
00:08:58,820 --> 00:09:01,420
Non-negotiable, as usual.

63
00:09:06,820 --> 00:09:08,260
What do we do now?

64
00:09:08,420 --> 00:09:10,260
That guy in the corner...

65
00:09:10,820 --> 00:09:12,260
Yeager is his name.

66
00:09:12,300 --> 00:09:15,540
He's some kind of a war hero.
Shot down five Germans in one day.

67
00:09:15,620 --> 00:09:18,020
He's a natural-born stick-and-rudder man.

68
00:09:18,340 --> 00:09:21,220
He's press-liaison man for the Air Force,
I think.

69
00:09:21,900 --> 00:09:23,620
Any problems with him?

70
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:25,420
- Only one.
- What's that?

71
00:09:26,020 --> 00:09:27,460
Holding him back.

72
00:09:32,140 --> 00:09:33,140
Major.

73
00:09:33,660 --> 00:09:35,020
- Hey there, Yeager.
- Sir.

74
00:09:35,940 --> 00:09:39,220
We were just talking to Slick
about the sound barrier.

75
00:09:39,660 --> 00:09:40,660
Is that right?

76
00:09:40,740 --> 00:09:43,420
We feel that the X-1
is ready to have a go at it.

77
00:09:43,540 --> 00:09:46,980
We think the X-1's got the answer
to go beyond Mach 1.

78
00:09:47,420 --> 00:09:49,060
If there is any beyond.

79
00:09:51,740 --> 00:09:53,500
So, what do you think?

80
00:09:54,380 --> 00:09:58,060
I'll tell you. Half these engineers
have never been off the ground.

81
00:09:58,180 --> 00:10:01,500
They might tell you that
the sound barrier's a brick wall.

82
00:10:01,580 --> 00:10:04,500
It'll rip your ears off
if you try to go through it.

83
00:10:04,700 --> 00:10:07,900
If you ask me,
I don't believe the damn thing even exists.

84
00:10:08,060 --> 00:10:10,140
Waitress, a drink for Mr. Yeager.

85
00:10:10,220 --> 00:10:11,740
No, thanks, I got one.

86
00:10:12,580 --> 00:10:15,100
So, do you think
you want to have a go at it?

87
00:10:15,420 --> 00:10:16,540
I might.

88
00:10:17,020 --> 00:10:21,500
But since, as you say,
this sound barrier doesn't really exist...

89
00:10:22,340 --> 00:10:23,580
how much...

90
00:10:23,740 --> 00:10:25,100
How much you got?

91
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:29,140
Just joking.
The Air Force is already paying me. Right?

92
00:10:30,460 --> 00:10:32,660
- Why sure, Yeager...
- So when do we go?

93
00:10:33,660 --> 00:10:35,420
How about tomorrow morning?

94
00:10:36,340 --> 00:10:37,580
I'll be there.

95
00:10:38,460 --> 00:10:39,940
See you there.

96
00:10:42,940 --> 00:10:44,780
How much are you paying him?

97
00:10:45,180 --> 00:10:47,580
I think it's $283.

98
00:10:47,940 --> 00:10:48,980
A week?

99
00:10:49,100 --> 00:10:50,460
A month.

100
00:10:50,940 --> 00:10:52,460
Well, that's not bad.

101
00:10:57,580 --> 00:11:00,220
First fellow to break the sound barrier...

102
00:11:00,340 --> 00:11:03,100
gets a free steak with all the trimmings.

103
00:11:05,780 --> 00:11:08,060
I'll have mine medium rare, please.

104
00:11:15,660 --> 00:11:18,460
Honey, you ever been caught
on the desert alone?

105
00:11:22,860 --> 00:11:24,300
I never have.

106
00:11:26,620 --> 00:11:28,540
I don't think I ever will.

107
00:11:31,020 --> 00:11:33,780
Never met the man
who could catch me out there.

108
00:11:34,140 --> 00:11:35,580
I'm half jackrabbit.

109
00:11:38,700 --> 00:11:40,380
Forget it, flyboy.

110
00:11:41,260 --> 00:11:43,540
You'd never catch me.

111
00:11:44,380 --> 00:11:45,820
I believe I will.

112
00:11:47,260 --> 00:11:48,860
Can't be done.

113
00:12:07,380 --> 00:12:09,300
Could I ask you something?

114
00:12:11,700 --> 00:12:13,300
Forget it, sweetie.

115
00:12:14,100 --> 00:12:15,540
She's his wife.

116
00:12:24,860 --> 00:12:26,740
Come on, baby.

117
00:12:29,220 --> 00:12:32,700
Yeah! Come on. Go, go.

118
00:12:34,980 --> 00:12:36,980
Glennis! I'm gonna get you!

119
00:12:39,180 --> 00:12:40,660
Come back here!

120
00:12:46,540 --> 00:12:48,020
Can't hide from me!

121
00:14:02,140 --> 00:14:04,820
- 'Morning, tiger.
- What have you two been up to?

122
00:14:06,420 --> 00:14:07,900
Where's Ridley?

123
00:14:08,180 --> 00:14:09,940
Over there waiting on you.

124
00:14:14,460 --> 00:14:15,860
Can I talk to you?

125
00:14:18,900 --> 00:14:21,140
I got a little problem.

126
00:14:22,900 --> 00:14:26,540
A horse threw me last night
and I dinged up my goddamn ribs.

127
00:14:26,780 --> 00:14:27,780
How bad?

128
00:14:27,860 --> 00:14:30,740
I feel like I broke a couple
of the sons of bitches.

129
00:14:31,420 --> 00:14:34,940
I won't be able to lean over
to shut the door. Got any ideas?

130
00:14:35,100 --> 00:14:36,500
Your left side okay?

131
00:14:38,540 --> 00:14:42,340
I don't want these guys to know
because they'll find somebody else to fly.

132
00:14:42,420 --> 00:14:44,900
- I'll try to fix you a handle.
- Thanks, man.

133
00:14:52,540 --> 00:14:54,780
Can you help me out?
I got a small emergency.

134
00:14:54,860 --> 00:14:58,900
I need to borrow your broom handle.
Just hold this right here.

135
00:15:07,580 --> 00:15:09,060
I think that'll work.

136
00:15:09,940 --> 00:15:11,180
Thank you, sir.

137
00:15:23,540 --> 00:15:25,300
Punch a hole in the sky.

138
00:15:26,580 --> 00:15:28,060
I'll be right back.

139
00:15:31,940 --> 00:15:33,380
- 'Morning!
- Good morning, sir.

140
00:15:33,460 --> 00:15:34,780
How are you feeling?

141
00:15:34,860 --> 00:15:36,340
Oh, just about right.

142
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:38,900
There she is, partner.
All bridled, saddled and ready to go.

143
00:16:40,220 --> 00:16:41,780
You got any Beemans?

144
00:16:42,020 --> 00:16:43,540
Yeah, I got a stick.

145
00:16:43,700 --> 00:16:45,660
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

146
00:16:45,740 --> 00:16:46,900
Fair enough.

147
00:16:59,180 --> 00:17:00,380
Hey, look.

148
00:17:00,980 --> 00:17:04,660
Stick this in the handle.
Take your good arm and just whang it.

149
00:17:05,500 --> 00:17:06,940
Okay, thanks, buddy.

150
00:18:24,260 --> 00:18:26,060
Pre-drop checklist complete.

151
00:18:26,380 --> 00:18:28,140
Ten, nine...

152
00:18:38,140 --> 00:18:39,140
Drop!

153
00:18:42,660 --> 00:18:44,220
There you go, buddy.

154
00:18:48,540 --> 00:18:50,700
Put your spurs to her, Chuck.

155
00:19:15,860 --> 00:19:17,580
Mach.91.

156
00:19:34,540 --> 00:19:35,580
.92.

157
00:19:40,380 --> 00:19:41,740
.93.

158
00:19:47,180 --> 00:19:48,780
Hit a mild buffet there.

159
00:19:49,020 --> 00:19:50,740
Just the usual instability.

160
00:19:52,300 --> 00:19:54,860
Ridley, make a note here,
would you, if you got...

161
00:19:54,900 --> 00:19:58,020
nothing better to do.
Elevator effectiveness regained.

162
00:20:05,700 --> 00:20:07,260
.95.

163
00:20:10,820 --> 00:20:12,340
.96.

164
00:20:18,100 --> 00:20:19,300
More buffeting.

165
00:20:20,380 --> 00:20:21,620
More commotion.

166
00:20:21,780 --> 00:20:23,300
Getting wobbly here.

167
00:20:27,220 --> 00:20:28,380
.98.

168
00:20:29,340 --> 00:20:31,020
She's getting real active.

169
00:20:39,900 --> 00:20:41,020
.99!

170
00:20:51,660 --> 00:20:53,060
What's that sound?

171
00:20:59,300 --> 00:21:01,060
He bought the farm.

172
00:21:03,620 --> 00:21:05,900
That's it. We're back to square one.

173
00:21:08,340 --> 00:21:09,540
Wait a minute.

174
00:21:17,020 --> 00:21:19,420
Ridley, make another note, would you?

175
00:21:20,300 --> 00:21:22,660
Must be something wrong
with the Mach meter.

176
00:21:22,740 --> 00:21:24,500
Jumped plumb off the scale.

177
00:21:25,180 --> 00:21:26,780
Gone screwy on me.

178
00:21:27,100 --> 00:21:29,180
You bust it, we'll fix it.

179
00:21:29,380 --> 00:21:31,780
Personally, I think you're seeing things.

180
00:21:34,300 --> 00:21:37,820
Could be. I'm still going upstairs
like a bat out of hell.

181
00:21:42,460 --> 00:21:43,740
We did it!

182
00:21:44,340 --> 00:21:46,700
We finally broke the sound barrier.

183
00:21:47,220 --> 00:21:48,540
We did it!

184
00:22:24,820 --> 00:22:27,620
I want to place a long-distance call
to Los Angeles.

185
00:22:27,700 --> 00:22:29,020
Who are you calling?

186
00:22:29,140 --> 00:22:30,140
The press!

187
00:22:30,220 --> 00:22:33,620
This is big news.
The sound barrier's been broken.

188
00:22:33,700 --> 00:22:35,380
No, sir. No press.

189
00:22:35,700 --> 00:22:38,260
No word of this is to go
beyond the flight line.

190
00:22:38,420 --> 00:22:42,060
What's going on? This is big news.
We need coverage of this.

191
00:22:42,180 --> 00:22:43,980
No, sir. Sorry, no press.

192
00:22:44,180 --> 00:22:46,460
Those are orders. National security.

193
00:22:46,580 --> 00:22:48,020
But the war's over!

194
00:22:48,340 --> 00:22:51,380
Look, pal, maybe they don't want
someone to know.

195
00:22:51,740 --> 00:22:52,700
Who?

196
00:22:53,140 --> 00:22:54,540
The Russians, maybe.

197
00:22:54,700 --> 00:22:56,820
But they're our allies!

198
00:22:57,140 --> 00:23:01,940
Well, anyway, someone figured it out
that way, and that's the way it is.

199
00:23:03,060 --> 00:23:04,540
Chuck, you're our man!

200
00:23:05,420 --> 00:23:07,100
You're the fastest man alive!

201
00:23:07,180 --> 00:23:09,060
We want you to fly more planes for us.

202
00:23:09,180 --> 00:23:11,620
We want you to fly all our planes!

203
00:23:12,140 --> 00:23:14,580
What you been doing, hedgehopping?

204
00:23:53,260 --> 00:23:54,940
Word will get out, Major.

205
00:23:55,020 --> 00:23:57,620
Maybe not to the press
or the general public.

206
00:23:57,940 --> 00:24:01,980
But soon, every fighter jock, rocket ace,
and rat-racer in the country...

207
00:24:02,060 --> 00:24:06,580
will be headed this way, wanting
to push the outside of the envelope...

208
00:24:07,020 --> 00:24:09,900
and get to the top of the pyramid.

209
00:24:35,180 --> 00:24:37,340
Edwards Air Force Base.

210
00:24:37,420 --> 00:24:39,300
This is the place to be, hon.

211
00:24:39,420 --> 00:24:42,740
They're going faster, farther
and higher here than anywhere else.

212
00:24:48,140 --> 00:24:50,220
I'll tell you something else, too.

213
00:24:50,420 --> 00:24:54,820
We'll climb right up that ladder,
just like we did at Langley.

214
00:24:55,660 --> 00:24:56,620
We?

215
00:24:57,740 --> 00:24:59,020
You mean you.

216
00:24:59,820 --> 00:25:01,580
Hon, we're a team!

217
00:25:01,900 --> 00:25:03,860
I move up, you move up.

218
00:25:04,420 --> 00:25:06,580
Right to the top of the old pyramid.

219
00:25:08,340 --> 00:25:09,500
Slow down, Gordo.

220
00:25:09,580 --> 00:25:11,900
Come on now, you're scaring the girls.

221
00:25:12,020 --> 00:25:15,060
You're scaring the girls. You are!

222
00:25:18,900 --> 00:25:19,860
Come on, Trudy.

223
00:25:20,140 --> 00:25:22,540
Who's the best pilot you ever saw?

224
00:25:24,460 --> 00:25:26,580
Who's the best pilot you ever saw?

225
00:25:32,780 --> 00:25:34,700
You're looking at him, baby.

226
00:25:38,700 --> 00:25:40,340
Come on, cheer up.

227
00:25:41,100 --> 00:25:43,620
Hey, have I ever let you down?

228
00:28:16,780 --> 00:28:18,020
Hi there, pops.

229
00:28:20,500 --> 00:28:22,980
Pancho's, eh? Damn, look who's here.

230
00:28:33,820 --> 00:28:36,620
Deke, that's 62 men...

231
00:28:37,060 --> 00:28:38,940
in the last 36 weeks.

232
00:28:40,540 --> 00:28:42,380
You know what that averages?

233
00:28:46,020 --> 00:28:48,500
Is that Gus Grissom from Langley Field?

234
00:28:49,780 --> 00:28:52,660
What is an ace like you
doing in a place like this?

235
00:28:52,740 --> 00:28:54,780
Well, if it ain't Hot Dog.

236
00:28:55,700 --> 00:28:56,900
Gordo...

237
00:28:57,780 --> 00:28:59,420
- Cooper, right?
- Yeah.

238
00:29:00,180 --> 00:29:04,060
Gordo thinks he's one of those
hot-dog pilots you hear so much about.

239
00:29:04,340 --> 00:29:06,100
You got a short memory.

240
00:29:06,300 --> 00:29:10,620
I am not one of them hot-dog pilots.
I am the Hot Dog Man himself.

241
00:29:11,060 --> 00:29:14,940
I guess you're too shy to tell this guy
how I used to wax your tail.

242
00:29:17,500 --> 00:29:18,780
Wax my tail?

243
00:29:20,540 --> 00:29:22,780
Hot Dog, you were just in my shadow.

244
00:29:23,580 --> 00:29:25,500
That's where you'll always be.

245
00:29:25,740 --> 00:29:28,020
What are you two rookies going to have?

246
00:29:29,180 --> 00:29:30,180
Rookies?

247
00:29:32,380 --> 00:29:34,300
Now hold on, sis.

248
00:29:35,100 --> 00:29:38,220
You are looking
at a whole new ballgame here now.

249
00:29:39,620 --> 00:29:42,420
In a few years I bet you're even
going to immortalize us...

250
00:29:42,500 --> 00:29:45,260
by putting our pictures up there
on your wall.

251
00:29:50,780 --> 00:29:53,020
Did I say something wrong?

252
00:29:53,460 --> 00:29:56,860
I'll tell you. We got two categories
of pilots around here.

253
00:29:57,340 --> 00:30:00,540
We got your prime pilots
that get all the hot planes.

254
00:30:00,660 --> 00:30:04,540
And we got your pudknockers
who dream about getting the hot planes.

255
00:30:05,580 --> 00:30:08,660
Now what are you two pudknockers
going to have?

256
00:30:13,660 --> 00:30:14,900
Scotch.

257
00:30:16,860 --> 00:30:19,580
You know what happened!
The machine broke.

258
00:30:19,660 --> 00:30:22,060
It didn't, it's the man.
He was dead before he went up.

259
00:30:22,140 --> 00:30:24,220
Don't talk about it here.

260
00:30:44,220 --> 00:30:46,460
Good one. Now fire it in here.

261
00:30:47,940 --> 00:30:49,420
Look at old Yeager.

262
00:30:50,140 --> 00:30:53,340
On top of the pyramid
for five goddamn years.

263
00:30:53,980 --> 00:30:56,980
Every time somebody goes faster,
he just goes up again.

264
00:30:58,100 --> 00:31:00,380
He stays the fastest man alive.

265
00:31:05,620 --> 00:31:06,860
You know...

266
00:31:07,500 --> 00:31:08,700
sometimes...

267
00:31:09,580 --> 00:31:12,660
all it takes is just the sound
of a truck starting.

268
00:31:14,260 --> 00:31:15,300
I think:

269
00:31:16,060 --> 00:31:17,660
"That's the crash truck."

270
00:31:24,220 --> 00:31:25,180
Anyway...

271
00:31:25,980 --> 00:31:28,020
I'm really glad we could talk.

272
00:31:28,700 --> 00:31:31,700
I thought I was the only one
who had these nightmares.

273
00:31:33,180 --> 00:31:34,340
Yeah. Me, too.

274
00:31:35,180 --> 00:31:38,460
Nobody ever wants to talk
about anything around here.

275
00:31:38,780 --> 00:31:40,700
Everybody's always trying to...

276
00:31:41,940 --> 00:31:44,700
"maintain an even strain."

277
00:31:46,300 --> 00:31:50,580
Well, you marry a fighter jock
and you marry the military.

278
00:31:52,060 --> 00:31:53,620
I'll tell you one thing.

279
00:31:54,140 --> 00:31:56,660
The military owes me for all this.

280
00:31:57,140 --> 00:31:59,540
One day I expect the military
to make good.

281
00:32:04,340 --> 00:32:07,380
Well, it sure ain't your average dull life.

282
00:32:08,860 --> 00:32:10,660
I went East for a reunion...

283
00:32:10,740 --> 00:32:13,940
and all my friends could talk about
was their husbands' work.

284
00:32:14,060 --> 00:32:18,260
How dog-eat-dog and cutthroat it was
on Madison Avenue...

285
00:32:19,180 --> 00:32:20,700
places like that.

286
00:32:23,740 --> 00:32:25,340
Cutthroat?

287
00:32:27,060 --> 00:32:29,660
I wondered how they would have felt...

288
00:32:30,620 --> 00:32:33,620
if each time their husband
went in to make a deal...

289
00:32:33,940 --> 00:32:37,740
there was a one in four chance
he wouldn't come out of the meeting.

290
00:32:42,540 --> 00:32:45,300
I'm going home to my folks in San Diego.

291
00:32:48,300 --> 00:32:49,780
What did Gordo say?

292
00:32:50,900 --> 00:32:53,260
He "maintained an even strain."

293
00:32:58,900 --> 00:33:00,020
Look at them.

294
00:33:01,620 --> 00:33:04,060
You'd think they were talking
about sports.

295
00:33:10,860 --> 00:33:11,820
Men...

296
00:33:13,140 --> 00:33:16,180
Sometimes they're just such... assholes.

297
00:33:28,780 --> 00:33:31,460
Sometimes they sure are
handy assholes, though.

298
00:33:32,180 --> 00:33:33,540
Yeah, sometimes...

299
00:33:35,780 --> 00:33:37,100
Sometimes.

300
00:33:41,740 --> 00:33:43,140
You want a hot dog?

301
00:33:49,260 --> 00:33:51,180
I'm leaving, Gordo.

302
00:33:57,460 --> 00:33:58,700
Look at that!

303
00:33:59,220 --> 00:34:01,740
Yeah, that's the D-558 Phase Two.

304
00:34:02,060 --> 00:34:03,580
Scott Crossfield.

305
00:34:03,660 --> 00:34:06,260
It sure as hell is. Jesus!

306
00:34:09,420 --> 00:34:11,420
He scorched that one, didn't he?

307
00:34:14,900 --> 00:34:17,020
He's pushing the outside of the envelope.

308
00:34:17,140 --> 00:34:19,020
He must be going for a record.

309
00:34:19,100 --> 00:34:21,180
He's shooting for Mach 2, I heard.

310
00:34:24,020 --> 00:34:28,020
On the 50th anniversary
of the Wright Brothers' historic flight...

311
00:34:28,420 --> 00:34:31,780
another historic flight takes place
as Scott Crossfield...

312
00:34:32,060 --> 00:34:35,860
streaks across the skies
over the high desert in California.

313
00:34:36,140 --> 00:34:37,260
Mach 2.

314
00:34:37,380 --> 00:34:40,180
Almost 1,500 miles per hour...

315
00:34:40,340 --> 00:34:42,540
and a new world record!

316
00:34:42,860 --> 00:34:44,940
It's a field day for the press.

317
00:34:45,020 --> 00:34:47,660
Congratulations come
from a previous record holder...

318
00:34:47,740 --> 00:34:52,220
as he shakes the hand
of the fastest man alive, Scott Crossfield.

319
00:34:52,580 --> 00:34:55,500
And there's a comradeship of speed.

320
00:34:55,660 --> 00:34:58,620
To Scott Crossfield, the fastest man alive.

321
00:35:00,140 --> 00:35:02,140
To the D-558 Phase Two.

322
00:35:04,140 --> 00:35:06,140
I'll tell you a quick one.

323
00:35:06,220 --> 00:35:08,020
The one about the newlyweds...

324
00:35:08,100 --> 00:35:11,100
who didn't know the difference
between Vaseline and putty.

325
00:35:11,620 --> 00:35:13,460
All their windows fell out.

326
00:35:17,260 --> 00:35:19,340
Compliments of Pancho's, Scotty.

327
00:35:22,460 --> 00:35:24,340
The real test wasn't Mach 2.

328
00:35:24,500 --> 00:35:28,500
I guess that demon lives out
at about 2.3 on your Mach meter.

329
00:35:29,620 --> 00:35:31,980
Yeah, but Mach 2 was the magic number.

330
00:35:32,460 --> 00:35:36,740
Like 60 homers, like batting.400,
like the four-minute mile.

331
00:35:37,380 --> 00:35:39,500
The press likes a nice round number.

332
00:35:39,660 --> 00:35:42,780
After that, they don't care,
until the next magic number.

333
00:35:42,900 --> 00:35:46,380
You need more than speed records.
You need coverage.

334
00:35:46,700 --> 00:35:47,860
Coverage?

335
00:35:48,140 --> 00:35:51,620
You mean them root weevils
that crawl around popping off cameras?

336
00:35:51,860 --> 00:35:53,900
Those root weevils write history.

337
00:35:54,140 --> 00:35:57,860
Let them write the history,
and let the pilots fly the planes.

338
00:35:59,500 --> 00:36:00,580
Pilots.

339
00:36:24,060 --> 00:36:26,660
You know what really makes
your rocket ships go up?

340
00:36:26,740 --> 00:36:30,180
The aerodynamics would take
so long to explain to you that...

341
00:36:30,340 --> 00:36:31,340
Funding.

342
00:36:31,420 --> 00:36:33,420
That's what makes your ships go up.

343
00:36:33,500 --> 00:36:35,100
I'll tell you something.

344
00:36:35,660 --> 00:36:37,180
And you guys, too.

345
00:36:37,740 --> 00:36:40,220
No bucks, no Buck Rogers.

346
00:36:40,900 --> 00:36:43,420
Whoever gets the funding
gets the technology.

347
00:36:43,500 --> 00:36:46,340
Whoever gets the technology stays on top.

348
00:36:46,460 --> 00:36:48,060
Flyboy, let's dance.

349
00:36:48,820 --> 00:36:50,300
I'll drink to that.

350
00:37:21,540 --> 00:37:24,220
He'll be going after Crossfield soon,
won't he?

351
00:37:24,620 --> 00:37:25,860
No, he won't.

352
00:37:26,020 --> 00:37:29,180
He'll be going after that demon
that lives in the thin air.

353
00:38:08,140 --> 00:38:09,540
You got any Beemans?

354
00:38:09,900 --> 00:38:13,340
Even before you hit Mach 2,
she'll be unforgiving on you.

355
00:38:13,580 --> 00:38:16,300
So take it easy.
Wring her out a little bit this time.

356
00:38:16,380 --> 00:38:17,380
You got any gum?

357
00:38:17,500 --> 00:38:18,820
Yeah, I got me a stick.

358
00:38:18,900 --> 00:38:21,180
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

359
00:38:21,500 --> 00:38:23,060
- Fair enough.
- Thank you.

360
00:38:38,220 --> 00:38:39,580
Okay, drop her.

361
00:38:39,820 --> 00:38:41,860
All right, here we go again.

362
00:38:46,060 --> 00:38:46,860
Drop!

363
00:38:57,020 --> 00:38:58,660
Number 3 coming on.

364
00:39:06,540 --> 00:39:09,100
Got seven seconds on 150 right now.

365
00:39:27,980 --> 00:39:29,820
I've got you in sight, Chuck.

366
00:39:30,500 --> 00:39:32,020
Going out of sight...

367
00:39:32,580 --> 00:39:33,540
now!

368
00:39:40,100 --> 00:39:41,340
Mach 1.

369
00:39:51,460 --> 00:39:52,500
Number 4.

370
00:39:57,460 --> 00:39:58,780
Here goes Mach 2.

371
00:39:59,300 --> 00:40:00,420
2. 1.

372
00:40:00,660 --> 00:40:01,900
Sorry, Scotty.

373
00:40:03,540 --> 00:40:04,860
You got her now, buddy.

374
00:40:04,940 --> 00:40:06,500
You can ease it back.

375
00:40:07,460 --> 00:40:08,700
Bring it on in.

376
00:40:08,860 --> 00:40:10,540
I'm pushing the envelope.

377
00:40:11,820 --> 00:40:13,540
See where that demon lives.

378
00:40:33,140 --> 00:40:35,020
Come in, Chuck.

379
00:40:37,020 --> 00:40:38,420
Say again. Over.

380
00:40:38,500 --> 00:40:40,260
Do you read? Over.

381
00:40:42,660 --> 00:40:45,180
Damn! He's uncorked it!

382
00:40:45,940 --> 00:40:47,300
Mayday! Mayday!

383
00:40:47,460 --> 00:40:49,220
Alert all ground crews.

384
00:40:53,660 --> 00:40:55,300
Talk to me!

385
00:40:56,380 --> 00:40:58,740
Mayday! Mayday! Alert the ground crews.

386
00:41:01,860 --> 00:41:02,860
Come in!

387
00:41:05,420 --> 00:41:07,340
Do you read me? Over.

388
00:41:18,540 --> 00:41:20,220
I'm fighting bad here.

389
00:41:21,980 --> 00:41:25,020
I'm down to 25,000 over Tehachapi.

390
00:41:28,580 --> 00:41:31,380
I don't know if I can make it
back to base or not.

391
00:41:32,580 --> 00:41:33,820
What happened?

392
00:41:33,940 --> 00:41:36,540
Think I must have bust the canopy
with my head.

393
00:41:36,860 --> 00:41:38,380
I'm getting okay now.

394
00:41:41,060 --> 00:41:43,940
We sure chased that old demon this time.

395
00:41:44,860 --> 00:41:46,860
That's as fast as a man can go.

396
00:41:48,700 --> 00:41:50,300
What's next, Ridley?

397
00:42:28,580 --> 00:42:29,780
It's called Sputnik.

398
00:42:29,860 --> 00:42:31,740
We know. Sit down.

399
00:42:37,340 --> 00:42:39,260
And as I was saying...

400
00:42:39,940 --> 00:42:43,420
whoever controls
the high ground of space...

401
00:42:43,940 --> 00:42:45,660
will control the world.

402
00:42:46,340 --> 00:42:50,300
The Roman Empire controlled
the world because it could build roads.

403
00:42:50,700 --> 00:42:54,300
Later, the British Empire was dominant
because it had ships.

404
00:42:55,700 --> 00:42:59,380
In the air stage, we were powerful
because we had the airplane.

405
00:43:00,820 --> 00:43:04,220
Now the Communists have established
a foothold in outer space.

406
00:43:04,780 --> 00:43:08,180
Soon they'll have space platforms
to drop nuclear bombs on us...

407
00:43:08,300 --> 00:43:10,500
like rocks from a highway overpass.

408
00:43:11,020 --> 00:43:13,860
How the hell did they get ahead of us?

409
00:43:14,020 --> 00:43:15,980
Gentlemen, I think we're ready.

410
00:43:21,300 --> 00:43:23,780
Is there a loose plug over there anywhere?

411
00:43:26,420 --> 00:43:28,060
Here it is. I'll get it.

412
00:43:28,260 --> 00:43:30,860
Senator Johnson's right.
This is Armageddon.

413
00:43:31,140 --> 00:43:33,940
The decisive battle
between the forces of good and evil.

414
00:43:34,020 --> 00:43:36,740
We're engaged in a struggle for survival.

415
00:43:39,060 --> 00:43:41,260
This footage was assembled from...

416
00:43:41,540 --> 00:43:44,220
sources operating under deep cover
at great risk.

417
00:43:44,340 --> 00:43:45,300
Very great!

418
00:43:45,500 --> 00:43:48,780
We're fortunate this material
did not perish with a couple of men.

419
00:43:48,860 --> 00:43:51,980
This is secret footage
of the Russian Korabl rocket...

420
00:43:52,060 --> 00:43:55,780
and these are the German scientists
that they captured after the war.

421
00:43:55,860 --> 00:43:58,860
Was it their German scientists
who got them up there first?

422
00:44:00,660 --> 00:44:02,300
No, it was not, Senator.

423
00:44:02,380 --> 00:44:05,060
Our Germans are better
than their Germans.

424
00:44:05,580 --> 00:44:08,580
That's Titov on the right
and on the left is Gagarin.

425
00:44:08,740 --> 00:44:11,420
No, Titov's on the left.
Gagarin's on the right.

426
00:44:13,140 --> 00:44:15,540
They bear a great resemblance
to each other.

427
00:44:15,660 --> 00:44:20,060
If the Soviets ever do put a man up there,
it will be one of these two.

428
00:44:20,220 --> 00:44:22,140
Most likely, the one on the left.

429
00:44:22,220 --> 00:44:23,500
- Gagarin.
- Titov.

430
00:44:24,820 --> 00:44:26,540
Isn't that their chief designer?

431
00:44:26,620 --> 00:44:28,180
We know very little about him.

432
00:44:28,300 --> 00:44:30,700
- Let us see him again.
- Here's some more of him.

433
00:44:30,780 --> 00:44:33,740
They've developed a program
of stupendous dimensions...

434
00:44:33,820 --> 00:44:36,300
and he is clearly the genius behind it.

435
00:44:38,220 --> 00:44:40,700
I, for one, do not intend to go to sleep...

436
00:44:41,060 --> 00:44:43,260
by the light of a Communist moon.

437
00:44:46,900 --> 00:44:48,940
Get that moron off of there!

438
00:44:52,860 --> 00:44:55,580
We could have orbited
a satellite a year ago...

439
00:44:55,700 --> 00:44:57,700
if we had been given a green light.

440
00:44:57,780 --> 00:45:01,380
Now we must get something up there
quick and dirty, any way at all.

441
00:45:01,540 --> 00:45:02,620
Well, what?

442
00:45:02,940 --> 00:45:06,700
By combining our available rockets,
the Redstone, the Atlas...

443
00:45:06,980 --> 00:45:09,260
I agree that we could launch a pod.

444
00:45:10,220 --> 00:45:11,260
A pot?

445
00:45:11,420 --> 00:45:12,420
A pod.

446
00:45:12,860 --> 00:45:14,140
A capsule.

447
00:45:14,260 --> 00:45:16,780
Now, we will be in full control of this pod.

448
00:45:16,940 --> 00:45:19,140
It will go up like a cannonball...

449
00:45:19,220 --> 00:45:21,660
and come down like a cannonball...

450
00:45:21,980 --> 00:45:24,380
splashing down in the ocean...

451
00:45:24,580 --> 00:45:27,900
with a parachute to spare the life
of the "specimen" inside.

452
00:45:28,860 --> 00:45:30,140
Spaceman?

453
00:45:30,460 --> 00:45:31,620
"Specimen."

454
00:45:33,780 --> 00:45:35,900
Well, what kind of "specimen"?

455
00:45:37,380 --> 00:45:38,460
A tough one.

456
00:45:39,580 --> 00:45:41,220
Responsive to orders.

457
00:45:42,580 --> 00:45:44,220
I had in mind a chimp.

458
00:45:44,820 --> 00:45:45,820
"Jimp"?

459
00:45:46,020 --> 00:45:47,940
Well, what the hell is a "jimp"?

460
00:45:48,260 --> 00:45:51,540
A chimp. A chimpanzee, Senator. An ape.

461
00:45:52,220 --> 00:45:55,900
The first American into space
is not going to be a chimpanzee.

462
00:45:57,380 --> 00:46:00,100
Who would you put into space,
Mr. President?

463
00:46:00,300 --> 00:46:04,020
We have film of some people
we think are strong candidates.

464
00:46:04,180 --> 00:46:07,180
We'd like to run it by you
and stimulate some thinking.

465
00:46:08,620 --> 00:46:12,300
These are people we felt
would be excellent in the splashdown.

466
00:46:12,500 --> 00:46:14,300
We like the one on the right.

467
00:46:14,380 --> 00:46:17,660
- No, on the left.
- On the right. Don't embarrass me!

468
00:46:17,740 --> 00:46:22,100
These people are very experienced with
machinery and have their own helmets.

469
00:46:22,380 --> 00:46:23,580
Is that a factor?

470
00:46:23,700 --> 00:46:25,100
As you'll see...

471
00:46:25,500 --> 00:46:28,420
they're quite comfortable
in conditions of flame.

472
00:46:29,380 --> 00:46:33,540
Now this is personnel
who have very well-developed equilibrium.

473
00:46:35,140 --> 00:46:37,500
Good middle ear. Also very nice people.

474
00:46:37,580 --> 00:46:38,940
Very easy to work with.

475
00:46:39,020 --> 00:46:41,940
With some work,
they could be very responsive to orders.

476
00:46:42,020 --> 00:46:44,780
This is my first choice.
The man with the hood.

477
00:46:44,900 --> 00:46:49,380
Since he works without eyesight,
his other senses are sharpened.

478
00:46:49,540 --> 00:46:52,780
In space there'll be little need
for eyeballing at any rate.

479
00:46:52,860 --> 00:46:55,460
The cannonball effect you mentioned...

480
00:46:55,740 --> 00:46:58,420
We were basically thinking about...

481
00:46:58,500 --> 00:47:00,460
putting a couple into orbit.

482
00:47:00,700 --> 00:47:02,780
Possibly adds emotional stability.

483
00:47:03,460 --> 00:47:06,700
This individual combines many
plus factors that we mentioned.

484
00:47:06,820 --> 00:47:10,740
Ease with flames, comfort at heights
and agility in the splashdown phase.

485
00:47:10,820 --> 00:47:13,100
Also, he is available as of the 15th.

486
00:47:15,380 --> 00:47:17,180
I want test pilots!

487
00:47:17,820 --> 00:47:19,940
Test pilots? No, you can't deal with them.

488
00:47:20,020 --> 00:47:23,060
I'm sure we can do better
with another type of man...

489
00:47:23,260 --> 00:47:24,940
any other type of man.

490
00:47:25,180 --> 00:47:26,820
A more manageable type.

491
00:47:26,940 --> 00:47:28,860
It will only complicate things.

492
00:47:28,940 --> 00:47:31,380
With a man we must guarantee
a safe return.

493
00:47:31,460 --> 00:47:34,340
Mr. President, I think
you'd be wise to reconsider.

494
00:47:35,020 --> 00:47:35,820
No, Lyndon.

495
00:47:36,220 --> 00:47:37,220
Test pilots?

496
00:47:37,300 --> 00:47:39,100
We'll be heading for some air bases.

497
00:47:39,180 --> 00:47:40,740
Not just some air bases.

498
00:47:40,900 --> 00:47:44,260
The one with the great test pilots.
There's only one place to go.

499
00:47:45,500 --> 00:47:48,900
I was there once before
and I hoped I'd never have to go back.

500
00:47:49,460 --> 00:47:53,660
It's a god-forsaken spot on the roof
of the high desert in California.

501
00:47:54,180 --> 00:47:57,500
A prehistoric throwback
of an airfield called Edwards.

502
00:47:57,860 --> 00:48:00,380
They've got a weird, mad-monk squadron.

503
00:48:00,820 --> 00:48:03,340
They live in rat shacks, terrible conditions.

504
00:48:03,420 --> 00:48:06,660
Corrugated tin, bare bones, low rent.

505
00:48:07,340 --> 00:48:09,260
This is the joint they hang out in.

506
00:48:09,340 --> 00:48:11,460
Pancho's Happy Bottom Riding Club.

507
00:48:11,780 --> 00:48:13,980
It's called Happy Bottom Riding Club?

508
00:48:14,340 --> 00:48:16,260
How'd it get a name like that?

509
00:48:16,700 --> 00:48:17,980
Ask Pancho.

510
00:48:18,300 --> 00:48:19,700
- Lock up?
- Yeah.

511
00:48:21,020 --> 00:48:24,380
We're meeting the Liaison Officer.
They are expecting us.

512
00:48:24,460 --> 00:48:25,980
They? Who's "they"?

513
00:48:26,220 --> 00:48:27,380
The best...

514
00:48:28,820 --> 00:48:29,820
Give me that!

515
00:48:30,020 --> 00:48:32,100
- The best test pilots in the world.
- Here?

516
00:48:33,060 --> 00:48:35,140
They got some kind of brotherhood.

517
00:48:36,260 --> 00:48:38,380
They think they got the right stuff.

518
00:48:38,500 --> 00:48:40,540
What stuff? Heroism, bravery?

519
00:48:40,900 --> 00:48:42,740
There any snakes around here?

520
00:48:42,820 --> 00:48:44,300
Yeah. In the bushes.

521
00:48:44,580 --> 00:48:48,380
Heroism and bravery are part of it.
But seems to be more to it.

522
00:48:48,900 --> 00:48:50,380
What do they say it means?

523
00:48:50,500 --> 00:48:53,340
They don't say anything.
They don't talk about it.

