take a few photos of us, would you?

1039
01:37:31,700 --> 01:37:35,700
Which one of you is going to be
the first one to be launched into space?

1040
01:38:10,900 --> 01:38:12,420
Here he is.

1041
01:38:12,980 --> 01:38:14,780
Captain Ham.

1042
01:38:16,700 --> 01:38:19,300
Grinning like a possum
eating a sweet potato.

1043
01:38:21,820 --> 01:38:25,460
Does he look like the kind of guy
who'd put doo-doo in the capsule?

1044
01:38:26,620 --> 01:38:27,700
Ham in a can.

1045
01:38:30,060 --> 01:38:32,420
America's first astronaut. Look at him!

1046
01:38:33,060 --> 01:38:37,740
You take a monkey like this,
you can make him a democrat, a politician.

1047
01:38:40,020 --> 01:38:42,660
I think he's better looking than Crossfield.

1048
01:38:45,020 --> 01:38:48,460
How would you like to go up
with this guy as your copilot?

1049
01:39:55,180 --> 01:39:57,300
They've got a man up there. It's Gagarin.

1050
01:39:57,380 --> 01:39:58,820
We know. Sit down.

1051
01:40:32,660 --> 01:40:34,540
All right, give them a break.

1052
01:40:39,420 --> 01:40:42,340
Is it true you were ready to go
and the flight was cancelled?

1053
01:40:42,420 --> 01:40:44,580
Is it true we could've beaten the Russians?

1054
01:40:44,700 --> 01:40:47,740
Why didn't we send a man up
instead of a monkey?

1055
01:40:49,300 --> 01:40:50,940
I think we ought to be...

1056
01:40:51,220 --> 01:40:54,260
forthright, gracious,
and magnanimous and say...

1057
01:40:54,620 --> 01:40:56,980
the Russians beat the pants off us.

1058
01:40:57,220 --> 01:40:59,140
No sense in kidding ourselves about it.

1059
01:40:59,220 --> 01:41:02,180
But the space age has begun,
and there's plenty of work.

1060
01:41:02,260 --> 01:41:04,420
Who will be the second man in space?

1061
01:41:05,340 --> 01:41:08,500
You mean who will be
the first free man into space?

1062
01:41:09,500 --> 01:41:11,780
We know it'll be Glenn. Just tell us when.

1063
01:41:12,060 --> 01:41:13,140
That's a secret.

1064
01:41:14,420 --> 01:41:17,620
I'm tired of being "forthright,
gracious, and magnanimous."

1065
01:41:18,060 --> 01:41:20,660
I'm tired of stupid questions
from the press.

1066
01:41:20,980 --> 01:41:23,940
I'm tired of smocks,
of engineers telling us what we can't do.

1067
01:41:24,020 --> 01:41:26,500
I'm tired of everybody saying
we are not pilots.

1068
01:41:26,580 --> 01:41:28,180
I'm tired of monkeys.

1069
01:41:28,660 --> 01:41:31,860
Most of all, I'm sick and tired
of being second to those...

1070
01:41:32,500 --> 01:41:35,060
those darned Russians. It's time we...

1071
01:41:35,180 --> 01:41:36,700
Got someone up there!

1072
01:41:38,780 --> 01:41:39,860
Fucking A, bubba.

1073
01:41:39,940 --> 01:41:41,540
- Exactly.
- Let's talk to them.

1074
01:41:41,620 --> 01:41:43,340
Let's get this thing on the road.

1075
01:41:43,500 --> 01:41:45,260
I'm tired of messing around.

1076
01:41:46,260 --> 01:41:49,140
We'll just tell 'em we're ready.
We're ready to go.

1077
01:42:24,580 --> 01:42:28,740
In these three weeks since the Russian
Gagarin's flight surprised everybody...

1078
01:42:28,900 --> 01:42:31,300
one wretched event has followed another.

1079
01:42:31,460 --> 01:42:34,180
People have begun to say
our rockets always blow up...

1080
01:42:34,340 --> 01:42:36,380
our boys always botch it.

1081
01:42:36,460 --> 01:42:41,540
Some say this is not the time to try
desperate deeds to beat the Soviets.

1082
01:42:41,620 --> 01:42:42,940
The question really is:

1083
01:42:43,100 --> 01:42:46,180
Are we actually ready
to launch a man into space?

1084
01:42:46,380 --> 01:42:50,060
And yet out here at this very moment
sits a rocket, waiting in the night.

1085
01:42:50,140 --> 01:42:53,340
Soon, one American astronaut
will climb atop that rocket...

1086
01:42:53,420 --> 01:42:57,020
in what may be the greatest
death-defying stunt ever broadcast.

1087
01:43:00,340 --> 01:43:03,540
The identity of America's first astronaut
has been kept a secret...

1088
01:43:03,660 --> 01:43:05,540
until almost the final moment.

1089
01:43:05,660 --> 01:43:09,100
The question everyone has asked is:
Which one will be first?

1090
01:44:38,100 --> 01:44:39,620
Not very funny, John.

1091
01:44:41,940 --> 01:44:44,020
But I do appreciate it, John.

1092
01:44:44,500 --> 01:44:46,060
I surely do.

1093
01:44:48,260 --> 01:44:50,380
Vaya con Dios, José.

1094
01:45:00,100 --> 01:45:02,900
Dear Lord, please don't let me fuck up.

1095
01:45:03,020 --> 01:45:05,780
I didn't quite copy that. Say again, please.

1096
01:45:08,140 --> 01:45:10,020
I said, everything's A-okay.

1097
01:45:10,100 --> 01:45:12,460
Well, that's what I thought you said.

1098
01:45:13,740 --> 01:45:16,340
He said everything is A-okay.

1099
01:45:17,140 --> 01:45:20,780
He says everything is A-okay.
And there you have it.

1100
01:45:30,180 --> 01:45:33,220
Roger. Auto retro-jettison switch.

1101
01:45:35,420 --> 01:45:37,380
Retro-heater switch... off.

1102
01:45:39,140 --> 01:45:41,060
Retro-heater switch... off.

1103
01:45:41,660 --> 01:45:43,940
Landing-bag switch... auto.

1104
01:45:45,140 --> 01:45:48,500
Roger. Landing-bag switch... auto.

1105
01:45:49,860 --> 01:45:52,620
This is it, ladies. This is for Life magazine.

1106
01:45:56,140 --> 01:45:59,060
My God! They're going
after the diaper-service man.

1107
01:46:02,140 --> 01:46:03,300
Stop that! Stop it!

1108
01:46:05,940 --> 01:46:08,140
We don't have a diaper-service man.

1109
01:46:08,220 --> 01:46:10,820
Get back from the door.
I don't know them, really.

1110
01:46:12,060 --> 01:46:13,580
Oh, Louise, your lawn!

1111
01:46:14,060 --> 01:46:15,820
Leave those diapers alone!

1112
01:46:16,900 --> 01:46:18,220
Shut that door!

1113
01:46:19,500 --> 01:46:20,820
Why are they here?

1114
01:46:20,940 --> 01:46:22,380
What do they want?

1115
01:46:22,460 --> 01:46:25,140
We are here live at the house
of Louise Shepard...

1116
01:46:25,260 --> 01:46:28,660
wife of Astronaut Al Shepard,
who is about to go into space.

1117
01:46:34,380 --> 01:46:36,620
Wanted to keep you informed,
Mrs. Shepard.

1118
01:46:36,700 --> 01:46:39,180
Everything's A-okay.
Nothing to worry about.

1119
01:46:39,460 --> 01:46:40,540
Just some delays.

1120
01:46:40,940 --> 01:46:42,660
What kind of delays?

1121
01:46:43,140 --> 01:46:45,860
There's another hold from NASA,
another delay.

1122
01:46:46,180 --> 01:46:49,060
And Alan Shepard sits there
patiently waiting.

1123
01:46:49,340 --> 01:46:52,380
What can be going through
a man's mind at this moment?

1124
01:47:01,020 --> 01:47:02,460
I have to urinate.

1125
01:47:02,540 --> 01:47:03,660
Urinate?

1126
01:47:05,700 --> 01:47:08,100
Urinate? No. We did not think of that.

1127
01:47:08,220 --> 01:47:10,500
This is only a 15-minute flight.

1128
01:47:10,660 --> 01:47:12,700
The man's been up there for hours.

1129
01:47:12,860 --> 01:47:14,460
Could he do it in his suit?

1130
01:47:14,540 --> 01:47:17,100
It might be dangerous.
To introduce liquid...

1131
01:47:17,260 --> 01:47:21,060
into the pure oxygen of the capsule
and the pressure suit...

1132
01:47:21,300 --> 01:47:24,260
might cause a short circuit.
It could start a fire.

1133
01:47:24,420 --> 01:47:26,020
No. Tell him he cannot.

1134
01:47:30,180 --> 01:47:34,140
Listen, old buddy, they promise
we'll stop at the next gas station.

1135
01:47:34,620 --> 01:47:38,140
Request that you remain
in a holding pattern till then.

1136
01:47:49,020 --> 01:47:52,020
- You sure you just want a little smidgen?
- About a half a cup.

1137
01:47:52,060 --> 01:47:54,020
- And nothing in it?
- That's fine.

1138
01:47:54,100 --> 01:47:55,180
All right.

1139
01:47:57,260 --> 01:48:00,820
Alan had four cups of coffee
before he went to work this morning.

1140
01:48:07,700 --> 01:48:10,100
All this waiting is driving me crazy.

1141
01:48:13,460 --> 01:48:15,060
I had a little accident.

1142
01:48:32,820 --> 01:48:35,220
Request permission to relieve bladder.

1143
01:48:45,060 --> 01:48:47,380
Look, the man has got to go.

1144
01:48:49,340 --> 01:48:52,660
It's either that or we get the lug wrench
and pry him out.

1145
01:48:53,980 --> 01:48:55,380
Do it in the suit.

1146
01:49:00,340 --> 01:49:02,380
José, permission granted...

1147
01:49:02,460 --> 01:49:04,700
to wet your diapers anytime, son.

1148
01:49:16,540 --> 01:49:19,700
Suit thermometer says
Freon flow jumping from 30 to 45.

1149
01:49:20,060 --> 01:49:21,940
Left lower-chest sensor.

1150
01:49:26,300 --> 01:49:28,340
No short-out. Moving up back.

1151
01:49:32,340 --> 01:49:33,380
Well...

1152
01:49:33,860 --> 01:49:35,380
I'm a wetback now.

1153
01:49:37,780 --> 01:49:39,780
It is questionable if we can proceed.

1154
01:49:39,900 --> 01:49:44,180
I'm cooler than you are. Why don't you
fix your problems and light this candle!

1155
01:49:44,500 --> 01:49:46,900
He's right! Let's light this candle!

1156
01:49:47,060 --> 01:49:49,140
He surely is! Light the candle!

1157
01:49:50,460 --> 01:49:51,980
Resume the countdown.

1158
01:49:53,780 --> 01:49:54,940
All systems go.

1159
01:50:00,020 --> 01:50:01,380
T minus ten seconds...

1160
01:50:01,500 --> 01:50:04,140
nine, eight, seven...

1161
01:50:11,620 --> 01:50:12,660
Ignition.

1162
01:50:20,820 --> 01:50:22,540
You're on your way, José.

1163
01:50:23,140 --> 01:50:25,740
We have liftoff, and the clock is operating.

1164
01:50:34,380 --> 01:50:37,620
I think we'll be able to talk
to one of the astronauts' wives...

1165
01:50:37,700 --> 01:50:39,820
if not to Louise Shepard herself.

1166
01:51:04,300 --> 01:51:08,740
He has re-entered the Earth's atmosphere
and the g-forces should be building up.

1167
01:51:08,820 --> 01:51:11,020
Louise, he's coming down!

1168
01:51:12,900 --> 01:51:15,020
We almost missed this.

1169
01:51:19,500 --> 01:51:20,580
Eight.

1170
01:51:22,140 --> 01:51:23,540
That's nine.

1171
01:51:24,580 --> 01:51:25,820
I'm okay!

1172
01:52:14,740 --> 01:52:17,580
The Vice President,
who is Chairman of our Space Council...

1173
01:52:17,660 --> 01:52:20,540
and who bears great responsibilities
in this field...

1174
01:52:20,620 --> 01:52:22,900
the members of the House and Senate...

1175
01:52:22,940 --> 01:52:25,940
Space Committee,
who are here today to award you...

1176
01:52:27,500 --> 01:52:30,460
this decoration,
which has gone from the ground up.

1177
01:52:54,380 --> 01:52:55,980
What was Jackie like?

1178
01:52:57,020 --> 01:52:58,260
She's very nice.

1179
01:52:58,380 --> 01:53:00,540
We talked about all kinds of things.

1180
01:53:00,620 --> 01:53:02,180
My Gus goes up next.

1181
01:53:02,540 --> 01:53:04,620
I can't wait to talk to Jackie after that.

1182
01:53:04,700 --> 01:53:07,900
You'll love her. She's so nice.
We talked about the kids.

1183
01:53:25,740 --> 01:53:27,460
Mr. Shepard, sign here.

1184
01:53:32,340 --> 01:53:34,260
I never realized...

1185
01:53:34,900 --> 01:53:39,340
a gruff, mean son of a bitch like you
could be so popular.

1186
01:53:40,980 --> 01:53:43,180
How'd you get to go up before me?

1187
01:53:43,540 --> 01:53:45,620
Even before "Mr. Clean, the Marine."

1188
01:53:46,380 --> 01:53:48,580
Charm, Hot Dog. Pure charm.

1189
01:53:49,460 --> 01:53:50,740
Watch this.

1190
01:53:52,660 --> 01:53:54,500
Hey, sis, how are you doing?

1191
01:53:54,580 --> 01:53:56,260
So-so. How are you doing?

1192
01:53:56,660 --> 01:53:58,140
I ain't doing anymore.

1193
01:53:58,260 --> 01:54:01,300
Damn thing's dragging in the mud,
and I can't get it up.

1194
01:54:02,060 --> 01:54:04,020
Charm, Gus, that's pure charm.

1195
01:54:07,060 --> 01:54:08,860
How'd you like one of these?

1196
01:54:09,660 --> 01:54:11,980
I can get one of those from a dime store.

1197
01:54:12,060 --> 01:54:14,420
Not one that's been in outer space.

1198
01:54:15,060 --> 01:54:17,260
I'm taking these up with me tomorrow.

1199
01:54:18,260 --> 01:54:21,420
Would you like a souvenir
after I get written in history?

1200
01:54:21,540 --> 01:54:24,460
Well, I might, if it's been in outer space.

1201
01:54:25,300 --> 01:54:27,180
See you after outer space.

1202
01:54:37,940 --> 01:54:40,140
You got to think ahead to the future.

1203
01:54:40,820 --> 01:54:43,700
Folks have a taste for things
that have been there.

1204
01:54:46,500 --> 01:54:50,780
I'll give you one of these dimes
I'm taking up so you can play with it...

1205
01:54:52,020 --> 01:54:54,260
and dream about outer space.

1206
01:54:56,740 --> 01:55:00,140
Why don't you just make sure
you don't screw the pooch?

1207
01:55:04,020 --> 01:55:05,940
Oh, God, look at this.

1208
01:55:14,180 --> 01:55:15,580
Go get 'em, Deke!

1209
01:55:26,260 --> 01:55:29,460
Grissom has just reached the apex
of his flight into outer space...

1210
01:55:29,540 --> 01:55:32,020
and will be coming down
with the valuable data...

1211
01:55:32,100 --> 01:55:35,420
needed for the future flights
that will actually orbit the Earth.

1212
01:55:35,500 --> 01:55:38,220
He will be re-entering
the atmosphere now.

1213
01:56:17,820 --> 01:56:22,460
Liberty Bell 7, Liberty Bell 7,
this is Hunt Club 1. Over.

1214
01:56:23,140 --> 01:56:25,820
We're in orbit at this time
around the capsule.

1215
01:56:29,060 --> 01:56:31,260
Are you ready to come in and hook on?

1216
01:56:32,380 --> 01:56:34,820
Roger. This is Hunt Club 1...

1217
01:56:34,900 --> 01:56:37,580
waiting for your okay
to come in and hook on.

1218
01:56:42,900 --> 01:56:47,060
Roger. I've unplugged my suit,
so I'm kind of warm now.

1219
01:56:48,980 --> 01:56:50,740
Hunt Club 1. Roger.

1220
01:56:51,060 --> 01:56:52,380
One, roger.

1221
01:56:52,700 --> 01:56:55,580
Roger. Blow the hatch after we hook on.

1222
01:56:56,580 --> 01:56:59,540
All right, get ready.
Another 15 feet to the right.

1223
01:57:03,260 --> 01:57:05,700
If you're ready for me to blow the hatch...

1224
01:57:06,420 --> 01:57:08,340
I'll take my helmet off.

1225
01:57:09,980 --> 01:57:11,500
Say again, Liberty Bell.

1226
01:57:11,580 --> 01:57:13,940
Waiting for your okay to hook on.

1227
01:57:17,820 --> 01:57:19,380
Who designed this?

1228
01:57:20,700 --> 01:57:23,220
Say again, Liberty Bell. We can't hear you.

1229
01:57:23,380 --> 01:57:24,820
I can't get it off.

1230
01:57:27,700 --> 01:57:29,940
Liberty Bell, say again.

1231
01:57:30,100 --> 01:57:32,580
This is Hunt Club 1, waiting for your okay.

1232
01:57:39,340 --> 01:57:40,500
What happened?

1233
01:57:43,420 --> 01:57:46,420
It's all right. He's okay. Go for the capsule.

1234
01:57:46,740 --> 01:57:48,340
Help, I'm sinking!

1235
01:57:49,700 --> 01:57:52,300
Get the capsule. He can float in that suit.

1236
01:57:56,220 --> 01:57:58,180
We need the data in the capsule.

1237
01:57:58,260 --> 01:58:00,020
Throw down a line!

1238
01:58:09,860 --> 01:58:12,340
Help! Throw down the line!

1239
01:58:15,140 --> 01:58:16,740
Hey, I'm sinking!

1240
01:58:17,060 --> 01:58:18,820
Forget the fucking capsule!

1241
01:58:22,980 --> 01:58:25,220
We can't pull it. It's full of water.

1242
01:58:26,020 --> 01:58:28,580
Hey! Help me over here!

1243
01:58:34,380 --> 01:58:35,540
We've lost it!

1244
01:58:35,620 --> 01:58:37,060
Blow the cable!

1245
01:58:41,220 --> 01:58:42,860
Come back here, damn it!

1246
01:58:53,220 --> 01:58:54,980
Throw a line down.

1247
01:59:50,020 --> 01:59:51,540
I didn't do anything.

1248
01:59:52,740 --> 01:59:54,380
I was just lying there.

1249
01:59:55,140 --> 01:59:56,420
It just blew.

1250
02:00:00,260 --> 02:00:01,860
The hatch just blew.

1251
02:00:14,140 --> 02:00:16,860
It must have been a technical malfunction.

1252
02:00:18,260 --> 02:00:20,460
The capsule was rocking around a bit.

1253
02:00:20,860 --> 02:00:24,540
There were no loose items. I don't see
how I could have hit that button.

1254
02:00:26,540 --> 02:00:28,980
I was just lying there, flat on my back...

1255
02:00:29,060 --> 02:00:30,340
and it just blew.

1256
02:00:43,020 --> 02:00:45,020
Well, what do you think?

1257
02:00:48,620 --> 02:00:52,180
Explosive hatches have been
on jet fighters for ten years.

1258
02:00:52,660 --> 02:00:55,060
The things have been wrung inside out...

1259
02:00:55,380 --> 02:00:59,380
subjected to trial by heat,
by water, by shaking, pounding.

1260
02:00:59,900 --> 02:01:04,620
We even drop them from a height
of 100 feet onto concrete...

1261
02:01:05,620 --> 02:01:09,140
and not one of them has ever "just blown."

1262
02:02:18,460 --> 02:02:21,100
- Are we going to the White House?
- No.

1263
02:02:23,020 --> 02:02:24,940
Isn't the President coming?

1264
02:02:30,580 --> 02:02:32,780
No ticker-tape parade in New York?

1265
02:02:35,220 --> 02:02:37,580
Not even one in Mitchell, Indiana?

1266
02:02:43,060 --> 02:02:44,300
No Jackie?

1267
02:02:53,500 --> 02:02:56,340
By order of the President
of the United States...

1268
02:02:57,260 --> 02:02:59,700
the Distinguished Service Medal...

1269
02:03:00,340 --> 02:03:03,980
is awarded to Captain Virgil I. Grissom...

1270
02:03:05,900 --> 02:03:10,420
who distinguished himself by valor
above and beyond the call of duty.

1271
02:03:11,700 --> 02:03:13,100
These actions...

1272
02:03:13,780 --> 02:03:16,100
reflect great credit upon himself...

1273
02:03:16,780 --> 02:03:18,380
the Air Force...

1274
02:03:19,460 --> 02:03:22,180
and the United States of America.

1275
02:03:34,580 --> 02:03:35,860
You proud, boys?

1276
02:03:46,140 --> 02:03:49,220
Hey, look. They filled up the refrigerator.

1277
02:03:52,020 --> 02:03:53,420
Pretty good, huh?

1278
02:03:54,540 --> 02:03:55,620
Pretty good.

1279
02:03:56,260 --> 02:03:57,820
A full refrigerator!

1280
02:03:59,340 --> 02:04:01,980
I can see this afternoon
is shaping up just great!

1281
02:04:02,380 --> 02:04:04,860
And the rest of the day. Tomorrow, too!

1282
02:04:05,580 --> 02:04:07,500
What do they want me to do in here?

1283
02:04:08,460 --> 02:04:09,540
Cook?

1284
02:04:10,780 --> 02:04:13,140
Then risk my life and my kids'...

1285
02:04:13,220 --> 02:04:17,020
by dragging them across that highway
to the worst beach in Florida!

1286
02:04:17,900 --> 02:04:20,660
Oh, Gus, I wanted to eat
in the White House.

1287
02:04:21,780 --> 02:04:23,980
I wanted to talk to Jackie about...

1288
02:04:25,540 --> 02:04:26,660
things.

1289
02:04:28,380 --> 02:04:31,700
Well, look, I've got to go
to the Holiday Inn for some...

1290
02:04:32,660 --> 02:04:34,380
beer call with the guys.

1291
02:04:38,740 --> 02:04:41,100
All those years of test flying...

1292
02:04:42,140 --> 02:04:46,060
and all those times I waited
and all those times you weren't there!

1293
02:04:47,700 --> 02:04:49,540
The military promised...

1294
02:04:50,140 --> 02:04:54,020
and now they are welshing
on that damn compact.

1295
02:04:55,020 --> 02:04:57,540
Look, I am finally
"Mrs. Honorable Astronaut."

1296
02:04:58,020 --> 02:05:00,100
But they are treating me like I'm...

1297
02:05:01,900 --> 02:05:04,260
Honorable
"Mrs. Squirming Hatch Blower!"

1298
02:05:04,420 --> 02:05:06,180
I didn't do anything wrong!

1299
02:05:06,540 --> 02:05:10,980
The hatch just blew! It was a glitch!
It was a technical malfunction!

1300
02:05:11,340 --> 02:05:13,540
Why in hell won't anyone believe me?

1301
02:05:20,140 --> 02:05:21,700
I know that.

1302
02:05:27,020 --> 02:05:29,780
Gus, I mean are these the goodies?

1303
02:05:31,300 --> 02:05:33,620
Is this how the military pays off?

1304
02:05:38,660 --> 02:05:41,380
Oh, Gus, they owe you.

1305
02:05:44,300 --> 02:05:45,900
But they owe me, too.

1306
02:05:47,260 --> 02:05:48,620
They owe me.

1307
02:05:49,500 --> 02:05:51,940
They owe me, they owe me so much!

1308
02:06:32,260 --> 02:06:33,580
I love you.

1309
02:06:37,060 --> 02:06:41,180
We are here with Virgil I. Grissom
and his lovely wife, Betty.

1310
02:06:42,500 --> 02:06:45,020
Gus has just come back
from the second trip in space.

1311
02:06:45,100 --> 02:06:47,380
Betty, how do you feel about this trip?

1312
02:06:47,620 --> 02:06:49,220
I'm so proud of him.

1313
02:06:49,540 --> 02:06:51,220
I think he was wonderful.

1314
02:06:51,340 --> 02:06:53,380
We're all proud of Gus Grissom.

1315
02:06:53,540 --> 02:06:56,580
Gus, how do you feel about the trip?
Was it a success?

1316
02:06:56,900 --> 02:06:58,500
It was A-okay.

1317
02:07:01,060 --> 02:07:04,140
My God. He lost his capsule
but he's keeping his story.

1318
02:07:04,260 --> 02:07:06,380
To recap yesterday's dramatic events...

1319
02:07:06,660 --> 02:07:09,460
here we see America's
newest hero, Gus Grissom.

1320
02:07:09,540 --> 02:07:11,980
He is shouting to save the capsule first.

1321
02:07:13,220 --> 02:07:16,220
Pull that in flight test, it's all over for him.

1322
02:07:17,620 --> 02:07:20,580
He screwed the pooch, partner.
Plain and simple.

1323
02:07:21,100 --> 02:07:24,020
Sometimes you get a pooch
that can't be screwed.

1324
02:07:25,940 --> 02:07:28,740
The President's got his own problems
with the Bay of Pigs.

1325
02:07:28,820 --> 02:07:31,180
He doesn't want
the astronauts' image tarnished.

1326
02:07:31,300 --> 02:07:34,100
Nothing these guys do
is going to be called a failure.

1327
02:07:34,220 --> 02:07:35,980
These astronauts are our Davids.

1328
02:07:36,060 --> 02:07:40,060
You'd think the public would know they're
just doing what monkeys have done.

1329
02:07:43,700 --> 02:07:47,420
You think a monkey knows he's sitting
on a rocket that might explode?

1330
02:07:48,500 --> 02:07:50,620
These astronauts know that.

1331
02:07:52,620 --> 02:07:54,220
I'll tell you something.

1332
02:07:54,820 --> 02:07:57,700
It takes a special man to volunteer
for a suicide mission.

1333
02:07:57,780 --> 02:07:59,460
Especially when it's on TV.

1334
02:08:03,620 --> 02:08:05,500
Old Gus, he did all right.

1335
02:08:05,900 --> 02:08:08,020
Though the capsule was lost,
our new hero...

1336
02:08:08,100 --> 02:08:10,220
Astronaut Gus Grissom, was saved.

1337
02:08:10,940 --> 02:08:14,940
Now President Kennedy has started
an even more ambitious space program.

1338
02:08:15,300 --> 02:08:17,140
Those who came before us...

1339
02:08:17,700 --> 02:08:19,460
made certain this country...

1340
02:08:19,540 --> 02:08:22,900
rode the first waves
of the industrial revolution...

1341
02:08:23,900 --> 02:08:26,420
the first waves of modern invention...

1342
02:08:26,500 --> 02:08:28,420
and the first wave of nuclear power.

1343
02:08:28,900 --> 02:08:31,780
And this generation does not intend...

1344
02:08:32,300 --> 02:08:34,300
to founder in the backwash...

1345
02:08:34,580 --> 02:08:37,940
of the coming age of space.
We mean to be a part of it.

1346
02:08:38,300 --> 02:08:39,700
We mean to lead it.

1347
02:10:32,660 --> 02:10:34,860
You know, I always hated flying.

1348
02:10:37,580 --> 02:10:41,660
When I met you, you were already a pilot,
so I never had a complaint coming.

1349
02:10:43,060 --> 02:10:46,020
When you went up in those planes,
me and the kids...

1350
02:10:51,180 --> 02:10:54,460
We never had any insurance
except a couple months' pay.

1351
02:10:56,740 --> 02:10:59,340
I always hated all that talk
about insurance.

1352
02:11:01,100 --> 02:11:04,380
The government spends
all kinds of time and money...

1353
02:11:04,460 --> 02:11:07,060
teaching pilots how to be fearless.

1354
02:11:09,700 --> 02:11:12,780
But they don't spend a penny
teaching you how to be...

1355
02:11:13,580 --> 02:11:15,820
the fearless wife of a test pilot.

1356
02:11:20,620 --> 02:11:22,380
But I guess I liked it.

1357
02:11:28,620 --> 02:11:31,140
I guess I liked the kind of man who could...

1358
02:11:32,140 --> 02:11:34,300
push the outside of the envelope.

1359
02:11:36,940 --> 02:11:38,060
Flyboy.

1360
02:11:41,100 --> 02:11:45,540
But I never could stand a man
who was one of those "remember-whens."

1361
02:11:46,220 --> 02:11:50,180
Those bitter guys that just sit around
thinking about old times.

1362
02:11:56,900 --> 02:11:58,740
If I ever see that happen...

1363
02:12:02,500 --> 02:12:04,700
I'm going right out the front door.

1364
02:12:08,900 --> 02:12:10,660
And you'll never catch me.

1365
02:12:12,260 --> 02:12:15,140
I'm a fearless man,
but I'm scared to death of you.

1366
02:12:15,460 --> 02:12:17,060
No, you're not.

1367
02:12:18,420 --> 02:12:19,900
But you ought to be.

1368
02:12:41,180 --> 02:12:42,500
What is it?

1369
02:12:43,980 --> 02:12:45,940
The Russians have sent Titov up.

1370
02:12:46,060 --> 02:12:47,180
Titov's up.

1371
02:12:47,820 --> 02:12:48,700
How long?

1372
02:12:48,780 --> 02:12:49,740
A day.

1373
02:12:50,060 --> 02:12:52,340
A day? A whole day?

1374
02:12:52,500 --> 02:12:54,860
He's orbiting over our country right now.

1375
02:12:55,700 --> 02:12:58,100
We need a man in orbit or it's all over.

1376
02:12:58,420 --> 02:13:01,380
We're scrapping the Redstone
and going with the Atlas.

1377
02:13:01,460 --> 02:13:03,140
You know what that means.

1378
02:13:03,460 --> 02:13:06,060
We haven't had too much luck
with that rocket.

1379
02:13:06,380 --> 02:13:08,940
We can't take all the precautions we'd like.

1380
02:13:09,300 --> 02:13:11,060
- It'll be dangerous.
- We're ready.

1381
02:13:11,140 --> 02:13:12,820
I said it'll be dangerous.

1382
02:13:12,900 --> 02:13:16,260
- I said we're ready. 100 percent.
- Thank you.

1383
02:13:28,820 --> 02:13:32,620
Inside this trim,
modest suburban home is Annie Glenn...

1384
02:13:32,940 --> 02:13:34,980
wife of Astronaut John Glenn...

1385
02:13:35,300 --> 02:13:39,500
sharing the anxiety and pride
of the world at this tense moment...

1386
02:13:39,860 --> 02:13:43,660
but in a private and crucial way
that only she can understand.

1387
02:13:50,260 --> 02:13:53,420
The Vice President would like
to see Mrs. Glenn.

1388
02:13:53,940 --> 02:13:55,620
He's asking for you again.

1389
02:13:56,620 --> 02:13:58,220
Tell them no.

1390
02:13:58,900 --> 02:14:00,820
I'm sorry, she says no.

1391
02:14:00,940 --> 02:14:03,020
You don't understand. It is very important.

1392
02:14:03,100 --> 02:14:05,060
The Vice President must see her.

1393
02:14:07,540 --> 02:14:09,900
We are told after the mission's success...

1394
02:14:09,980 --> 02:14:13,460
the Vice President will come here
and speak with Annie Glenn.

1395
02:14:13,740 --> 02:14:16,860
Meanwhile, John Glenn waits
for the weather to clear...

1396
02:14:16,940 --> 02:14:19,540
so he can undertake this historic mission.

1397
02:14:20,020 --> 02:14:22,020
You know what the Russians want?

1398
02:14:24,500 --> 02:14:27,180
They want our peckers in their pockets.

1399
02:14:30,500 --> 02:14:31,900
She still says no.

1400
02:14:33,900 --> 02:14:37,380
Didn't you tell her I'll bring in ABC-TV...

1401
02:14:37,900 --> 02:14:40,500
NBC-TV, CBS-TV?

1402
02:14:41,500 --> 02:14:44,580
Her words, and mine,
will be heard by millions.

1403
02:14:54,220 --> 02:14:55,740
Where are they going?

1404
02:14:57,780 --> 02:14:59,820
I think the flight's been cancelled.

1405
02:14:59,900 --> 02:15:01,100
Cancelled?

1406
02:15:03,780 --> 02:15:05,300
That's perfect.

1407
02:15:05,580 --> 02:15:09,300
I will go in and console her
on nationwide TV.

1408
02:15:10,420 --> 02:15:12,300
I'll pay her a sympathy call.

1409
02:15:39,820 --> 02:15:43,780
The Vice President would like to make
a sympathy call if he could.

1410
02:15:47,180 --> 02:15:49,620
- No? What do you mean, "No"?
- I mean, "No."

1411
02:15:50,060 --> 02:15:52,100
What do you mean, "No"?

1412
02:15:52,460 --> 02:15:54,500
Somebody get NASA on the line.

1413
02:15:54,660 --> 02:15:58,700
I'm going to lean on NASA.
I'm going right to the top!

1414
02:15:59,900 --> 02:16:01,500
- To the top.
- Damn right!

1415
02:16:01,900 --> 02:16:04,420
They better tell her to play ball!

1416
02:16:12,940 --> 02:16:14,780
There's a problem with your wife.

1417
02:16:14,860 --> 02:16:16,580
- Is it serious?
- We think it is.

1418
02:16:16,740 --> 02:16:19,220
There's a phone hookup,
we've got her on it.

1419
02:16:27,620 --> 02:16:29,620
It's me. Are you all right?

1420
02:16:29,700 --> 02:16:30,980
What's wrong?

1421
02:16:31,500 --> 02:16:33,100
Johnson...

1422
02:16:35,140 --> 02:16:36,740
wants... me...

1423
02:16:40,660 --> 02:16:42,820
on T... V.

1424
02:16:42,980 --> 02:16:44,140
The Vice President?

1425
02:16:44,220 --> 02:16:46,500
Tell her to let him in with the networks.

1426
02:16:46,860 --> 02:16:48,180
It's coverage.

1427
02:16:52,460 --> 02:16:54,020
It's important, John.

1428
02:16:54,500 --> 02:16:55,700
It means a lot.

1429
02:17:01,540 --> 02:17:02,700
Listen to me.

1430
02:17:04,940 --> 02:17:07,260
If you don't want the Vice President...

1431
02:17:07,580 --> 02:17:10,780
or the networks,
or anyone else in our house, that's it!

1432
02:17:11,220 --> 02:17:13,940
As far as I'm concerned,
they are not coming in!

1433
02:17:14,020 --> 02:17:17,220
And I will back you up 100 percent,
and you tell them that!

1434
02:17:19,100 --> 02:17:23,060
I don't want Johnson or the others
to even put a toe in our house.

1435
02:17:29,580 --> 02:17:33,820
You tell them that Astronaut John Glenn
told you to say that.

1436
02:17:42,060 --> 02:17:43,820
I'll talk to you soon.

1437
02:17:48,860 --> 02:17:50,220
You can't do that!

1438
02:17:50,420 --> 02:17:52,460
The Vice President's head of the program!

1439
02:17:52,580 --> 02:17:54,300
You must think of the program!

1440
02:17:54,380 --> 02:17:55,780
You are out of line!

1441
02:17:55,860 --> 02:17:57,860
- I'm out of line?
- Yes, sir!

1442
02:17:59,020 --> 02:18:00,220
I run the show here.

1443
02:18:00,380 --> 02:18:01,980
We'll see about that!

1444
02:18:02,380 --> 02:18:05,740
And I'm thinking of changing
the order of flight assignments!

1445
02:18:06,540 --> 02:18:07,900
Who will you get?

1446
02:18:08,140 --> 02:18:10,020
You heard what he said.

1447
02:18:15,460 --> 02:18:17,060
Take it easy, fellows.

1448
02:18:17,420 --> 02:18:18,820
Step aside, pal.

1449
02:18:30,380 --> 02:18:31,660
Pilots!

1450
02:18:35,020 --> 02:18:36,940
Pansies! Cows!

1451
02:18:39,500 --> 02:18:40,940
Gladiolas!

1452
02:18:41,260 --> 02:18:44,980
Isn't there anybody
who can deal with a housewife?

1453
02:19:10,060 --> 02:19:12,660
Waltzing Matilda,
I thought Hank Williams wrote it.

1454
02:19:12,780 --> 02:19:14,580
We don't know who wrote it.

1455
02:19:14,660 --> 02:19:16,340
It's Australian, right?

1456
02:19:24,780 --> 02:19:26,340
Who are you guys?

1457
02:19:29,700 --> 02:19:31,020
We're aborigines.

1458
02:19:36,460 --> 02:19:37,500
Who are you?

1459
02:19:37,580 --> 02:19:38,580
Me?

1460
02:19:40,980 --> 02:19:42,380
I'm an astronaut.

1461
02:19:46,180 --> 02:19:48,780
Well, what do you do here, Astronaut?

1462
02:19:49,340 --> 02:19:53,340
I'm here because a buddy of mine
is getting ready to...

1463
02:19:54,020 --> 02:19:56,540
fly overhead. Up in outer space.

1464
02:19:57,060 --> 02:19:59,580
And I'll be talking to him on that dish.

1465
02:20:00,660 --> 02:20:01,780
Fly over?

1466
02:20:02,540 --> 02:20:04,140
You blokes do that, too?

1467
02:20:05,020 --> 02:20:06,660
You do that yourself?

1468
02:20:07,100 --> 02:20:09,060
Not me, mate.

1469
02:20:09,780 --> 02:20:11,380
See that old bloke there?

1470
02:20:12,980 --> 02:20:14,060
He know.

1471
02:20:14,140 --> 02:20:15,620
He know the moon.

1472
02:20:16,420 --> 02:20:17,860
He know the star.

1473
02:20:18,860 --> 02:20:20,740
And he know the Milky Way.

1474
02:20:21,220 --> 02:20:22,980
He'll give you a hand.

1475
02:20:24,060 --> 02:20:25,220
He know.

1476
02:20:29,220 --> 02:20:31,900
We're gonna need all the help we can get.

1477
02:21:00,740 --> 02:21:03,300
Stand by for final ten-second count.

1478
02:22:02,340 --> 02:22:04,100
The clock is operating.

1479
02:22:04,860 --> 02:22:06,620
We're underway!

1480
02:22:11,780 --> 02:22:15,420
Good Lord, ride all the way.
Godspeed, John Glenn.

1481
02:23:27,140 --> 02:23:29,500
Zero-g, and I feel fine.

1482
02:23:31,300 --> 02:23:33,500
The capsule is turning around.

1483
02:23:36,900 --> 02:23:38,780
The view is tremendous!

1484
02:23:39,020 --> 02:23:43,220
I can see clear back,
a big cloud pattern, towards the Cape.

1485
02:23:43,300 --> 02:23:45,100
It's a beautiful sight!

1486
02:23:45,500 --> 02:23:49,820
Roger, Friendship 7.
You have a go, at least seven orbits.

1487
02:23:54,140 --> 02:23:57,100
Roger, Al. Understand,
go at least seven orbits.

1488
02:23:57,180 --> 02:23:58,780
This is Friendship 7.

1489
02:24:23,980 --> 02:24:27,300
Speed is 17,500 miles per hour...

1490
02:24:35,100 --> 02:24:37,340
and we're moving into night.

1491
02:24:57,420 --> 02:24:59,180
Full moon rising.

1492
02:25:03,140 --> 02:25:04,860
I can almost touch it.

1493
02:25:19,780 --> 02:25:22,460
Friendship 7, come in. Do you read?

1494
02:25:25,940 --> 02:25:27,820
Friendship 7, come in, please.

1495
02:25:28,220 --> 02:25:29,940
This sure was a short day.

1496
02:25:30,100 --> 02:25:31,740
Say again, please. Over.

1497
02:25:32,220 --> 02:25:34,780
That was the shortest day I've run into.

1498
02:25:35,300 --> 02:25:37,140
Kind of passes rapidly, huh?

1499
02:25:38,060 --> 02:25:39,020
Yes, sir.

1500
02:25:41,260 --> 02:25:44,340
I can see some lights down there
in Australia, Gordo.

1501
02:25:45,020 --> 02:25:46,500
Where are they from?

1502
02:25:46,780 --> 02:25:50,900
All of Perth and Rockingham
have turned their lights on for you.

1503
02:25:52,260 --> 02:25:55,380
And we have a few other lights turned on,
here and there.

1504
02:26:00,620 --> 02:26:02,340
They show up very well.

1505
02:26:02,900 --> 02:26:05,660
Thank everybody for turning them on,
will you?

1506
02:26:06,060 --> 02:26:08,780
We sure will, John. We sure will.

1507
02:26:25,100 --> 02:26:26,860
Heading towards daybreak.

1508
02:27:04,500 --> 02:27:06,700
Lot of cloud coverage today.

1509
02:27:14,100 --> 02:27:15,820
Man, it's beautiful.

1510
02:27:30,380 --> 02:27:32,300
Possibly it's the heat shield.

1511
02:27:32,620 --> 02:27:33,740
It's loose.

1512
02:27:36,380 --> 02:27:37,660
If it comes off...

1513
02:27:37,740 --> 02:27:40,300
If the heat shield comes off, he'll burn up.

1514
02:27:41,260 --> 02:27:43,260
He'll fry when he tries to re-enter.

1515
02:27:57,700 --> 02:27:59,300
Muchea, this is Cape.

1516
02:28:00,260 --> 02:28:01,980
We're showing some trouble.

1517
02:28:02,220 --> 02:28:05,300
We've got a warning light.
Possibly a loose heat shield.

1518
02:28:05,420 --> 02:28:07,620
Check your status lights immediately.

1519
02:28:25,900 --> 02:28:27,260
He's coming.

1520
02:28:29,020 --> 02:28:30,540
John, can you hear me?

1521
02:28:32,940 --> 02:28:34,860
Friendship 7, come in, please.

1522
02:28:35,100 --> 02:28:36,780
Try something. Anything.

1523
02:28:36,860 --> 02:28:38,100
Friendship 7, come in.

1524
02:29:11,580 --> 02:29:15,060
This is Friendship 7. Do you read me?

1525
02:29:16,900 --> 02:29:18,300
Wait a second.

1526
02:29:19,740 --> 02:29:21,940
I see something strange out here.

1527
02:29:22,100 --> 02:29:25,340
Oh! My goodness, what the heck is that?

1528
02:29:26,300 --> 02:29:29,340
Sparks and needles of some kind
all over the sky!

1529
02:29:29,660 --> 02:29:32,660
Hey, let me tell you what I'm in up here.

1530
02:29:32,980 --> 02:29:35,380
I'm in a mass of very small particles...

1531
02:29:35,620 --> 02:29:38,740
that are brilliantly lit up.
Like they're luminescent.

1532
02:29:38,940 --> 02:29:40,860
I never saw anything like it.

1533
02:29:41,340 --> 02:29:43,300
A shower of them coming by me now.

1534
02:29:43,380 --> 02:29:46,340
They're bright yellow.
They swirl around the capsule...

1535
02:29:46,420 --> 02:29:49,180
and they're brilliantly lighted.

1536
02:29:50,140 --> 02:29:52,860
Do you think they could be alive?

1537
02:29:55,060 --> 02:29:58,620
It sounds ridiculous,
but they look like fireflies or something.

1538
02:30:01,740 --> 02:30:04,700
Maybe some Air Force experiment
went amuck.

1539
02:30:04,980 --> 02:30:07,220
Could our astronomers have been wrong?

1540
02:30:07,580 --> 02:30:10,460
Hello, CapCom, do you read me?
This is miraculous!

1541
02:30:11,300 --> 02:30:14,460
Could it be those fireflies,
or whatever they are?

1542
02:30:14,900 --> 02:30:16,820
Of course not. Fireflies?

1543
02:30:19,380 --> 02:30:21,020
Roger, Friendship 7.

1544
02:30:22,580 --> 02:30:25,780
Will you correlate the actions
of the surrounding particles...

1545
02:30:25,900 --> 02:30:27,980
with that of your control jets?

1546
02:30:29,500 --> 02:30:30,940
Negative.

1547
02:30:31,540 --> 02:30:34,940
I do not think they were coming
from my control jets.

1548
02:30:36,060 --> 02:30:37,940
I'll tell you what I'll try to do.

1549
02:30:38,060 --> 02:30:40,780
I'll try to get some pictures
of these little guys.

1550
02:30:40,860 --> 02:30:42,420
Sounds like a good idea.

1551
02:30:42,900 --> 02:30:45,180
You guys probably think I'm nuts.

1552
02:30:46,300 --> 02:30:48,020
They're very beautiful.

1553
02:30:48,540 --> 02:30:50,500
Look like fireflies on a summer night.

1554
02:30:50,580 --> 02:30:52,300
They just dance around.

1555
02:31:28,300 --> 02:31:29,700
Get out of here!

1556
02:31:32,580 --> 02:31:34,580
Get out of here, you gadgets!

1557
02:31:37,060 --> 02:31:39,460
Heading into daybreak now. Another day.

1558
02:31:39,660 --> 02:31:41,580
Leaving the fireflies behind.

1559
02:31:41,940 --> 02:31:44,020
I have no idea what they were.

1560
02:31:44,940 --> 02:31:46,540
This is Friendship 7.

1561
02:31:47,660 --> 02:31:50,220
That was some night.
That was really exciting.

1562
02:31:50,300 --> 02:31:51,940
He's going into his third orbit.

1563
02:31:52,060 --> 02:31:55,060
How much longer are you going
to keep him in the dark?

1564
02:31:55,380 --> 02:31:56,620
What do we tell him?

1565
02:31:56,700 --> 02:31:59,660
He's a pilot.
Tell him the condition of his craft.

1566
02:32:05,220 --> 02:32:06,820
Glenn is in his third orbit...

1567
02:32:06,900 --> 02:32:09,500
and the flight is going
pretty much as planned.

1568
02:32:09,980 --> 02:32:11,300
No human individual...

1569
02:32:11,380 --> 02:32:13,820
has ever been so well prepared.

1570
02:32:14,020 --> 02:32:17,580
So far the keyword
on this textbook flight is "operational."

1571
02:32:17,740 --> 02:32:19,420
Everything is A-okay.

1572
02:32:21,380 --> 02:32:24,180
We haven't been too lucky
with the Atlas rocket.

1573
02:32:24,380 --> 02:32:27,820
Some say we haven't taken all
the safety precautions we'd like to.

1574
02:32:27,900 --> 02:32:29,060
Is this true?

1575
02:32:29,180 --> 02:32:30,860
No, it's absolutely not true.

1576
02:32:31,420 --> 02:32:33,940
The only critical point is the re-entry.

1577
02:32:34,380 --> 02:32:37,140
If the capsule is not at the correct angle...

1578
02:32:37,220 --> 02:32:40,820
with the blunt end and heat shield down,
it will burn up.

1579
02:32:41,180 --> 02:32:42,940
There is only one hope.

1580
02:32:43,260 --> 02:32:46,060
It might be possible to leave
the retro-rocket package...

1581
02:32:46,140 --> 02:32:48,060
which covers the heat shield, on.

1582
02:32:48,420 --> 02:32:53,020
The straps may be strong enough
to hold the heat shield in place.

1583
02:32:53,740 --> 02:32:55,460
But if this fails...

1584
02:32:57,060 --> 02:33:00,100
John, you're going to
fly-by-wire for re-entry.

1585
02:33:00,980 --> 02:33:04,500
We recommend you do the best
you can to keep a zero angle. Over.

1586
02:33:05,260 --> 02:33:07,180
Re-entry only three orbits? Over.

1587
02:33:07,540 --> 02:33:08,980
That is correct. Over.

1588
02:33:09,060 --> 02:33:11,180
Do you have a reason for this? Over.

1589
02:33:11,500 --> 02:33:14,820
Not at this time.
This is the judgment of Cape Flight.

1590
02:33:16,900 --> 02:33:17,900
Roger.

1591
02:33:18,740 --> 02:33:21,940
Do you have a time for going
to jettison retro? Over.

1592
02:33:24,340 --> 02:33:27,220
We are not sure your landing bag
is deployed.

1593
02:33:27,900 --> 02:33:31,340
We feel it is possible to re-enter
with the retro-package on.

1594
02:33:31,620 --> 02:33:35,020
We see no difficulty at this time
with that type of re-entry.

1595
02:33:35,100 --> 02:33:36,500
Do you read?

1596
02:33:37,340 --> 02:33:38,540
Roger.

1597
02:33:39,860 --> 02:33:41,300
Understand.

1598
02:33:42,620 --> 02:33:46,260
I'll start lining up as carefully as I can
in a minute.

1599
02:33:46,660 --> 02:33:51,260
See whether scanners will pick up
and correct it for good retro-fire attitude.

1600
02:33:52,140 --> 02:33:53,260
If not...

1601
02:33:53,940 --> 02:33:55,860
I'll correct it myself.

1602
02:33:57,540 --> 02:33:58,940
Roger, Friendship 7.

1603
02:34:07,860 --> 02:34:09,380
We're lined up.

1604
02:34:10,300 --> 02:34:11,620
Here we go.

1605
02:34:48,740 --> 02:34:50,340
What's that sound?

1606
02:34:50,620 --> 02:34:52,100
Humming. It's him.

1607
02:34:52,180 --> 02:34:54,100
It's all right. He does that.

1608
02:35:59,860 --> 02:36:01,220
- John...
- He can't hear you.

1609
02:36:01,780 --> 02:36:03,900
He's hit the ionization blackout.

1610
02:36:04,820 --> 02:36:07,780
No communications are possible
for a few minutes.

1611
02:36:10,380 --> 02:36:11,860
Then we'll know.

1612
02:36:20,820 --> 02:36:23,380
Friendship 7, this is Cape. Do you read?

1613
02:36:30,260 --> 02:36:32,340
This is Cape. Do you read?

1614
02:36:36,820 --> 02:36:40,180
Friendship 7, this is Cape. Do you read?

1615
02:36:40,580 --> 02:36:44,260
Automatic systems are not functioning.
He's in fly-by-wire...

1616
02:37:44,900 --> 02:37:46,420
Finally showed up.

1617
02:37:46,860 --> 02:37:49,020
The one with the big engine.

1618
02:37:50,700 --> 02:37:53,580
Boy, if we'd only had
one of those a few years back.

1619
02:37:54,740 --> 02:37:58,940
The bad news is the entire program's
probably going to be scrapped.

1620
02:37:59,980 --> 02:38:03,660
From now on, the astronaut boys
in Houston have got the only ticket.

1621
02:38:04,460 --> 02:38:08,020
Barring, of course, some unforeseen event.

1622
02:38:28,820 --> 02:38:31,900
The Russians set a new record
of 114,000 feet...

1623
02:38:31,980 --> 02:38:33,940
going straight off the ground.

1624
02:38:34,020 --> 02:38:36,620
Nobody cares about
that kind of record anymore.

1625
02:38:37,340 --> 02:38:40,340
All they want now
is capsules up in outer space.

1626
02:38:43,380 --> 02:38:47,340
I get a feeling this plane might be able
to beat that Russian record.

1627
02:38:50,180 --> 02:38:51,700
You might be right.

1628
02:39:37,500 --> 02:39:39,340
And here they come!

1629
02:39:48,740 --> 02:39:51,660
Looky here what I brought you!

1630
02:40:01,700 --> 02:40:03,780
Mr. And Mrs. John Glenn.

1631
02:40:08,660 --> 02:40:10,340
Alan Shepard.

1632
02:40:14,620 --> 02:40:16,620
Gus Grissom.

1633
02:40:19,140 --> 02:40:21,100
Scott Carpenter.

1634
02:40:23,380 --> 02:40:25,380
Deke Slayton.

1635
02:40:27,900 --> 02:40:29,860
Wally Schirra.

1636
02:40:30,940 --> 02:40:32,940
Mr. And Mrs. Gordon Cooper.

1637
02:40:33,460 --> 02:40:34,700
Smile, hon.

1638
02:40:35,700 --> 02:40:37,460
My fellow citizens...

1639
02:40:39,980 --> 02:40:44,060
America's Mercury astronauts!

1640
02:40:55,340 --> 02:40:58,220
Welcome to Houston, your new home.

1641
02:40:58,500 --> 02:41:03,060
Your neighbors here and I,
we'd like to give you this little barbecue...

1642
02:41:05,500 --> 02:41:07,020
Texas style!

1643
02:41:48,620 --> 02:41:52,860
Since you're relocating here,
to show appreciation for all you've done...

1644
02:41:53,220 --> 02:41:55,940
Mr. Sharp is contributing the land...

1645
02:41:56,020 --> 02:41:58,020
the contractors the homes...

1646
02:41:58,140 --> 02:42:00,980
and the department stores,
all the furnishings.

1647
02:42:01,660 --> 02:42:03,220
- That's wonderful.
- Thank you.

1648
02:42:03,300 --> 02:42:04,860
- Which one are you?
- Shepard.

1649
02:42:07,660 --> 02:42:10,180
Which one's Glenn? I want to meet him.

1650
02:42:11,780 --> 02:42:13,300
He's over there.

1651
02:42:13,540 --> 02:42:14,540
Excuse me.

1652
02:42:15,820 --> 02:42:16,820
Excuse me, too.

1653
02:42:22,260 --> 02:42:25,380
I'm going to the moon,
I swear to God, I'm on my way.

1654
02:42:28,940 --> 02:42:31,740
Hi, little gal.
Damned glad to meet you, too.

1655
02:42:31,940 --> 02:42:35,420
I heard an awful lot of good things
about you, gal.

1656
02:42:39,100 --> 02:42:40,300
- Howdy.
- How are you?

1657
02:42:40,380 --> 02:42:41,980
I want to meet you, too.

1658
02:42:43,060 --> 02:42:44,460
Sorry, little lady.

1659
02:42:44,660 --> 02:42:45,700
We got it.

1660
02:42:46,100 --> 02:42:48,860
Steak. All the trimmings.

1661
02:42:50,660 --> 02:42:52,540
Just like Pancho's.

1662
02:42:55,260 --> 02:42:57,180
Steak tastes about the same...

1663
02:42:57,940 --> 02:43:00,700
only there's a lot
more trimmings now, Gus.

1664
02:43:03,260 --> 02:43:04,740
You know, it's funny.

1665
02:43:05,700 --> 02:43:09,900
Here I am, I got $25,000 a year
for a magazine contract.

1666
02:43:10,820 --> 02:43:13,340
I got a free house with all the furnishings.

1667
02:43:13,420 --> 02:43:15,100
Got me a Corvette.

1668
02:43:16,060 --> 02:43:19,420
I got a free lunch from one end of America
to the other...

1669
02:43:20,420 --> 02:43:22,620
and I ain't even been up there yet.

1670
02:43:24,820 --> 02:43:25,820
I noticed that.

1671
02:43:25,900 --> 02:43:29,260
Oh, you noticed that?
You noticed I hadn't been up there yet?

1672
02:43:31,940 --> 02:43:34,300
They're saving the best for last.

1673
02:43:36,340 --> 02:43:38,900
Yeah, I guess so, Hot Dog. I guess so.

1674
02:43:41,260 --> 02:43:43,500
Just watch you don't screw the pooch.

1675
02:44:02,380 --> 02:44:06,780
We're talking to Gordon Cooper.
He will be the next to orbit the Earth.

1676
02:44:08,620 --> 02:44:13,260
Since you're the last of the original seven
and the least well known...

1677
02:44:13,380 --> 02:44:17,900
could you begin by telling us
who was the best pilot you ever saw?

1678
02:44:18,780 --> 02:44:21,100
Who is the best pilot I ever saw?

1679
02:44:28,180 --> 02:44:30,700
Who is the best pilot I ever saw?

1680
02:44:34,940 --> 02:44:36,460
I'll tell you.

1681
02:44:36,700 --> 02:44:41,260
I've seen a lot of them, and
most of them were pictures on a wall...

1682
02:44:41,340 --> 02:44:42,420
Excuse me, what'd you say?

1683
02:44:42,500 --> 02:44:46,540
I said, "pictures on a wall,"
back at some place that...

1684
02:44:48,700 --> 02:44:50,700
doesn't even exist anymore.

1685
02:44:53,780 --> 02:44:55,220
Some of them are...

1686
02:44:55,340 --> 02:44:57,260
right here in this room.

1687
02:44:58,860 --> 02:45:00,620
And some of them are...

1688
02:45:01,300 --> 02:45:05,260
they're still out there somewhere,
doing what they always do.

1689
02:45:05,380 --> 02:45:08,660
Going up each day
in a hurtling piece of machinery...

1690
02:45:08,780 --> 02:45:11,500
putting their hides out on the line...

1691
02:45:11,900 --> 02:45:14,180
hanging it out over the edge...

1692
02:45:14,420 --> 02:45:18,020
pushing back the outside
of that envelope and hauling it back.

1693
02:45:20,020 --> 02:45:21,580
But there was...

1694
02:45:22,140 --> 02:45:26,540
one pilot I once saw who I think
truly did have the right...

1695
02:45:26,620 --> 02:45:29,580
How close did you ever come
to not hauling it back?

1696
02:45:34,660 --> 02:45:36,940
Who is the best pilot I ever saw?

1697
02:45:37,260 --> 02:45:39,300
Well, you're looking at him.

1698
02:45:54,020 --> 02:45:54,980
Hey, Ridley!

1699
02:45:56,820 --> 02:45:58,580
You got any Beemans?

1700
02:46:00,020 --> 02:46:01,740
I might have me a stick.

1701
02:46:01,820 --> 02:46:04,460
Loan me some. I'll pay you back later.

1702
02:46:06,140 --> 02:46:07,460
Fair enough.

1703
02:46:08,780 --> 02:46:11,780
Think I see a plane over here
with my name on it.

1704
02:46:14,020 --> 02:46:15,620
Now you're talking.

1705
02:46:29,740 --> 02:46:31,140
Hey, what's that?

1706
02:46:31,380 --> 02:46:33,220
Anyone got clearance?

1707
02:46:36,860 --> 02:46:38,980
What kind of a plane is that?

1708
02:46:44,700 --> 02:46:47,580
Aircraft on ramp, did you file a flight plan?

1709
02:46:48,540 --> 02:46:51,500
Aircraft on ramp, did you file a flight plan?

1710
02:46:52,140 --> 02:46:55,620
I'm taking her up to wring her out a bit.
Any objections?

1711
02:46:55,740 --> 02:46:57,100
It's Yeager.

1712
02:46:59,420 --> 02:47:00,820
No objections.

1713
02:47:01,180 --> 02:47:03,020
You are clear to taxi.

1714
02:47:04,500 --> 02:47:06,580
He must have clearance. Right?

1715
02:47:06,780 --> 02:47:08,780
Yeah. Sure, he must.

1716
02:47:09,340 --> 02:47:10,860
It's here someplace.

1717
02:49:10,860 --> 02:49:13,060
Now, in honor of...

1718
02:49:13,380 --> 02:49:17,020
these, the greatest pilots
in the history of mankind...

1719
02:49:17,500 --> 02:49:21,340
it gives me great pleasure, great pride,
to present to you...

1720
02:49:21,980 --> 02:49:23,700
Miss Sally Rand!

1721
02:52:09,660 --> 02:52:11,580
Stretch it! Stretch it!

1722
02:52:12,260 --> 02:52:13,660
You can do it!

1723
02:52:15,260 --> 02:52:18,620
Just a little bit more. 104,000, here you go.

1724
02:52:23,820 --> 02:52:25,380
Christ Almighty!

1725
02:55:36,660 --> 02:55:38,300
Sir, over there.

1726
02:55:40,740 --> 02:55:42,100
Is that a man?

1727
02:55:45,140 --> 02:55:47,220
Yeah, you're damn right it is!

1728
02:56:51,180 --> 02:56:53,420
We hate to disturb you, buddy, but...

1729
02:56:54,540 --> 02:56:56,100
we've got a launch.

1730
02:56:59,020 --> 02:57:02,420
There's millions of people watching,
and we thought maybe...

1731
02:57:02,900 --> 02:57:05,820
Yep. Well, no sweat. Let's go.

1732
02:57:06,500 --> 02:57:09,620
I'm ready when you are, John, 100 percent.

1733
02:57:15,180 --> 02:57:17,100
Ten, nine...

1734
02:57:57,740 --> 02:57:59,500
Go.

1735
02:58:06,660 --> 02:58:08,900
Go, Hot Dog, go!

1736
02:58:13,540 --> 02:58:16,140
"Up we go into the wild blue yonder."

1737
02:58:16,500 --> 02:58:20,060
Thirty seconds and fuel is go,
oxygen is go...

1738
02:58:20,180 --> 02:58:23,300
cabin pressure on the top peg.
Altimeter is working.

1739
02:58:25,100 --> 02:58:26,980
Have a good ride, buddy. Go!

1740
02:58:31,500 --> 02:58:33,900
The sun is coming through the window.

1741
02:58:35,660 --> 02:58:38,540
Oh, Lord, what a heavenly light.

1742
02:58:51,020 --> 02:58:53,060
The Mercury program was over.

1743
02:58:53,700 --> 02:58:56,900
Four years later,
Astronaut Gus Grissom was killed...

1744
02:58:56,980 --> 02:58:59,620
along with Astronauts White and Chaffee...

1745
02:58:59,740 --> 02:59:02,740
when fire swept through
their Apollo capsule.

1746
02:59:03,740 --> 02:59:07,540
But on that glorious day in May, 1963...

1747
02:59:07,900 --> 02:59:11,260
Gordo Cooper went higher, farther...

1748
02:59:11,540 --> 02:59:13,940
and faster than any other American.

1749
02:59:14,420 --> 02:59:17,180
Twenty-two complete orbits
around the world.

1750
02:59:17,460 --> 02:59:20,700
He was the last American
ever to go into space alone.

1751
02:59:21,260 --> 02:59:23,100
And for a brief moment...

1752
02:59:23,420 --> 02:59:28,300
Gordo Cooper became the greatest pilot
anyone had ever seen.

